{[%evp 0,11,25,25,52,47,46,15,23,14,24,34,22,44]} 1. e4 c5 2. Nf3 (2. c3 {
The Alapin} d5 3. exd5 Qxd5 4. d4 Nf6 5. Nf3 e6 {This is our move order and
the start of a major tabiya. There are many other options like Bg4, Nc6, etc.
But after investigating a lot of time in this position, I figured out the text
move is quite intresting as well. As it allows us to play for the win!}) 2...
e6 3. c3 d5 4. exd5 Qxd5 5. d4 Nf6 6. Na3 $1 {The best variation against this
line.} (6. Bd3 {We will now postpone taking on d4 and White will run out of
moves soon.} Be7 $5 7. O-O O-O $1 8. Be3 (8. Qe2 cxd4 $1 {We have a new trick
of Nb4 now!} 9. cxd4 Nc6 {following up with Nb4 next. We are good}) (8. dxc5
Rd8 9. Bc2 Qxc5 10. Qe2 Nbd7 {With very good play. It is important to remember
to develop our knight on d7 and not c6 in this position. The positions are
often similar to french structures.}) (8. c4 {When they play c4 in such
positions there is no clear rule where the queen will retreat.} Qd7 {We went
there to keep Rd8 options open. It should be memorized as it is impossible to
find it over the board.} 9. dxc5 Rd8 10. Bc2 Qxd1 11. Rxd1 Rxd1+ 12. Bxd1 Bxc5
$132 13. Nc3 b6 {with a very comfortable position.}) 8... b6 $1 {We want to
wait for one more move to provoke Nbd2 so that he can never disturb our queen
with Nc3. If White wastes time we will simply play Bb7-Rd8 and typical play.} (
8... Rd8 $1 {is also playable.}) 9. Nbd2 cxd4 10. cxd4 (10. Bxd4 Bb7 {We have
a good version of the French defense. We want to trade the dark squared bishop
later.}) 10... Ba6 {We finally manage to force the trade of light squared
bishops.}) (6. Be3 $5 {This used to be the mainline. White wants to play with
an isolated queen's pawn.} cxd4 7. cxd4 {In terms of tempi, our queen on d5 is
not well placed. However, Black has found some ways to make this variation
playable.} (7. Qxd4 Nc6 8. Qxd5 Nxd5 {Black is doing very well. The pawn
majority on the queenside is irrelevant and the evaluation depends entirely on
the activity of his pieces.}) 7... Bb4+ (7... Nc6 {used to be the mainline.} 8. Nc3
Qd6 9. a3 Be7 10. Bd3 O-O 11. Qc2 {But this is honestly too much suffering.
And the brand new line is much better.}) 8. Nc3 O-O {This is a very concrete
position where tempi's matter a lot.} 9. Bd3 {Intending to castle. Now, we can
either play b6 or Bd7.} (9. a3 {would be a waste of time.} Bxc3+ 10. bxc3 Qa5
11. Bd2 Ne4) 9... b6 $1 (9... Bd7 $1 {with exactly the same idea of Bxc3 & Bb5.
} 10. O-O (10. Qe2 Bc6 11. O-O Qh5 {Once again, White can't play Be2 to
disturb our queen there and we have a good position.}) 10... Bxc3 11. bxc3 Bb5
{Executing our plan.} 12. Bxb5 Qxb5 13. Rb1 (13. Qb3 Qa6 14. Rab1 b6 {0-1 (44)
Ramirez Garcia,J-Swiercz,D/Barcelona ESP 2018/[,Giannis]}) 13... Qa6 14. Qb3 b6
15. c4 Nc6 {Everything is well supported and Black will soon start targeting
the the hanging pawns.}) 10. O-O (10. Qe2 {intending to stop Ba6. However,
White has a big problem which will be revealed soon.} Bb7 11. O-O Qh5 {White
wants to meet Qh5 with Be2, which is not possible now. And thats the main
drawback of Qe2.} 12. Ne5 Qxe2 13. Bxe2 Nbd7 {with a comfortable position. We
will consider trading on c3 next.}) 10... Bxc3 11. bxc3 Ba6 {Typical strategy
in this line. Black wants to trade the light squared bishops.} 12. Bxa6 (12.
Ne5 {is also possible, but we just follow our plans.} Bxd3 13. Qxd3 Nbd7 {
Black has good endgame prospects.}) (12. Rc1 {planning c4} Bxd3 13. Qxd3 Qxa2
14. c4 Qa4 {The pawn grab worked well and we will finish our development soon.}
) 12... Nxa6 13. Ne5 (13. Qd3 {attacking the a6-knight but we have a good
typical trick here.} Nc5 14. Qb5 Nce4 {Black got free activity and is certainly
better.}) 13... Nb8 {relocating our knight to d7.} 14. c4 Qb7 15. a4 Nc6 16.
Qf3 Rfc8 17. Rfb1 Qc7 {White's weak overextended pawns on d4,c4 & a4 will be
huge targets.}) (6. Be2 {Against this line - I suggest playing in the isolated
queen's pawn way. This works now only because White's bishop on e2 is
misplaced.} cxd4 {I recommend capturing it right now and just continuing with
normal development.} 7. cxd4 Nc6 8. Nc3 Qd6 9. O-O Be7 10. Be3 {Our plan is to
castle short and ideally play b6-Bb7.} (10. Bg5 O-O {Our plan is to next play
Nd5.} 11. a3 {stopping Nb4 ideas but we simply follow up with} (11. Rc1 Nd5 $1
{is no big deal. Black wants to trade all minor pieces.}) 11... Nd5 12. Bxe7
Ncxe7 13. Rc1 Nxc3 14. Rxc3 b6 15. Ne5 Bb7 $15 {Black is very solid and
White's IQP doesn't really give him any play on either side.}) (10. Nb5 $5 {
When I saw this move 30 years ago, I thought it was a legit try for advantage.
But slowly, I changed my thoughts and this move looks stupid to me now.} Qd8
11. Bf4 Nd5 {Attacking the Bishop and protecting c7.} 12. Bg3 {White's idea is
to control the g3-b8 diagonal.} O-O 13. Rc1 $1 (13. Qd2 b6 {Planning Bb7 and
Rac8 next with good play.}) 13... Bd7 $5) 10... O-O 11. Rc1 (11. Qd2 b6 {
Nb4-Nd5 is also another possible idea.} 12. Rfd1 Bb7 13. Rac1 Nb4 $5 {planning
Nd5 next. Black is doing great.}) 11... b6 $1 {Planning Bb7 next. We will
complete our development and White has to waste a move with Bd3 to make his IQP
sense.}) (6. Nbd2 $6 {is totally wrong as the knight is misplaced on d2. We
can simply play a better version of the IQP.} cxd4 7. Bc4 Qd6 8. Nxd4 a6 {
with very good play.}) (6. c4 {is harmless if you know some moves} Qd8 7. Be3
cxd4 8. Nxd4 Bb4+ 9. Nd2 O-O {We again have a good version of the french
defense.}) 6... a6 $5 {Whenever we see a Na3; ...a6 is always a good response.
There are many other options as well, but this is the easiest to play.} 7. Nc4
$1 {The best of the best choice. However, this is very rare to face it.} (7.
Nc2 $6 Nbd7 $5 {In these positions, I prefer delaying to take on d4. Black has
a good version of the french defense.} (7... Nc6 $5 {is also possible.})) (7.
Be2 $6 {simply hangs the a3-knight.} cxd4 8. cxd4 Bxa3 9. Qa4+ Bd7 $1 10. Qxa3
Bb5 $3 $15 {Black has a clear advantage.}) 7... Nbd7 {We will plan b5/b6,Be7 &
castle.} 8. Be2 {White is hoping to put his bishop on f3.} (8. Ne3 $6 Qc6 9.
Bd3 b6 $1 {Black will follow up with natural developing moves. He is completely
fine.}) (8. a4 {has also been tried to stop b5. But we can simply play ..b6} b6
9. Be2 Bb7 {Black's play looks more clear.}) 8... b5 9. Ne3 (9. Na5 Bd6 10. c4
bxc4 11. Nxc4 Bc7 $1 12. O-O Bb7 {0-1 (58) Drazic,S-Cheparinov, I/Bol CRO
2015/[,Giannis]}) (9. Nfd2 $6 Rb8 10. Bf3 Qf5 11. Ne3 Qf4 $1 {0-1 (16) Henris,
L-Kishnev,S/Antwerp 1999/EXT 2000/[,Giannis]}) 9... Qc6 10. O-O (10. Ne5 Qc7 {
We are protecting everything.} 11. Bf3 Bb7 12. Nxd7 Qxd7 13. Bxb7 Qxb7 {
White's knight on e3 is misplaced.}) 10... Bb7 11. a4 Be7 12. axb5 axb5 13.
Rxa8+ Bxa8 14. dxc5 Qxc5 $3 (14... Bxc5 $2 {would be a mistake in view of} 15.
Nd4 Bxd4 16. Qxd4 $16 {White is better.}) 15. Nc2 $5 (15. Bd2 Bxf3 $3 16. Bxf3
Ne5 17. Be2 O-O 18. Qb3 Rb8 $132 {with amazing counterplay!}) (15. Nd4 b4 $132
16. Qa4 O-O {Fortunately the complications favor us.}) 15... O-O 16. Be3 Qc7
17. Bxb5 Rb8 18. Bxd7 Nxd7 19. Bc1 Nf8 20. h3 Ng6 21. Re1 h6 $132 {Black has
strong control of the center which is giving him equal chances} *

