1. e4 c5 2. Nf3 (2. c3 d5 {our move order.} 3. exd5 Qxd5 4. d4 Nf6 5. Nf3 e6 {
Transposes.}) 2... e6 3. c3 d5 4. exd5 Qxd5 5. d4 Nf6 6. Be3 cxd4 7. cxd4 Bb4+
8. Nc3 (8. Nbd2 {would be altmost like a novelty but it doesn't really follows
the principles of isolated queens pawn. We will follow in typical fashion with}
O-O 9. Bd3 b6 10. O-O Bxd2 11. Qxd2 Ba6 12. Bxa6 Nxa6 {Black has a classical
advantage.}) 8... O-O 9. Bd3 Bd7 $1 {This is equally good with 9...b6!} 10. O-O
(10. Qe2 Bc6 {Executing our plan.} 11. O-O Qh5) 10... Bxc3 11. bxc3 Bb5 12. Ne5
Bxd3 13. Qxd3 Nc6 14. Nxc6 Qxc6 15. c4 {The position is equal but Black has
easier play.} (15. Rac1 b5) 15... Rac8 16. Rac1 h6 $1 {This move is absolutely
essential in these positions with hanging pawns! It opens the back rank and
stops Bg5. You can study the rest of the game by your own.} (16... Qe4 {
Also looks good.}) 17. Rfd1 Rfd8 18. h3 Qa6 19. Qb3 Rc6 20. Bf4 Rdc8 21. c5 b6
22. Bd6 Ne4 23. Be7 R6c7 24. Bh4 bxc5 25. d5 c4 26. Qe3 exd5 27. Rxd5 Qe6 28.
Rd4 Nc5 29. Rdxc4 Qxe3 30. fxe3 Ne6 31. Rxc7 Rxc7 32. Rb1 Rc2 33. a4 Nc5 34. a5
Ra2 35. Rb5 Ne4 36. Bd8 Ra1+ 37. Kh2 Nd2 38. Kg3 Nf1+ 39. Kf3 Nd2+ 40. Ke2 Ne4
41. Kd3 Nf2+ 42. Kc4 Rc1+ 43. Kd5 Rd1+ 44. Kc6 Ne4 45. Rd5 Rc1+ 46. Kb7 Nc3 47.
Rc5 Rb1+ 48. Kxa7 Nb5+ 49. Ka6 Nd6 50. Bb6 Ne4 51. Rc8+ Kh7 52. Rc4 Nd6 53. Rc6
Nf5 54. Kb7 Ne7 55. Rc7 Nd5 56. Rc5 Nxe3 57. a6 Ra1 58. a7 Nxg2 59. a8=Q Rxa8
60. Kxa8 Nf4 61. Kb7 Nxh3 62. Kc6 f6 63. Kd5 Ng5 64. Rc1 h5 65. Be3 Nf7 66. Ke4
h4 67. Rh1 g5 68. Kf5 Kg7 69. Bd4 Nh6+ 70. Ke6 Kg6 71. Bxf6 Ng4 72. Bd4 Nh6 73.
Ke5 Ng4+ 74. Ke4 Nh6 75. Rg1 Nf5 76. Be3 Ng3+ 77. Kf3 Kf5 78. Bf2 Ne4 79. Be1
h3 80. Bg3 g4+ 81. Ke2 Nxg3+ 82. Kf2 Ne4+ 83. Ke2 Kf4 84. Kf1 Ng3+ 85. Kf2 Nf5
86. Ke2 g3 87. Rh1 Kg4 88. Kf1 g2+ 0-1

