{[%evp 0,4,39,23,42,47,47] In this lecture, we will study the Closed Sicilian
after:} 1. e4 c5 2. Nc3 {and we will also cover other second move alternatives
for White:} (2. d4) (2. b3) (2. a3) (2. c4) (2. f4) (2. b4) {The Closed
Sicilian is a very important and serious Anti-Sicilian. We will meet it with}
2... a6 $1 {which is a sound and very practical choice.} ({For Najdorf players,
} 2... d6 {is the only alternative, because White can still decide to
transpose to the open Sicilian with Nf3 (or Nge2) and d4. 2...d6 is also sound,
but,  it allows two playable and annoying systems:} 3. f4 {with the Grand Prix
Attack} ({and} 3. d4 cxd4 4. Qxd4 Nc6 5. Qd2 {which was popularized by Magnus
Carlsen})) *

[Event "?"]
[Site "?"]
[Date "????.??.??"]
[Round "?"]
[White "Closed Sicilian 2...a6!"]
[Black "Theoretical Overview"]
[Result "*"]
[ECO "B23"]
[Annotator "GM Ioannis Papaioannou"]
[PlyCount "24"]
[EventDate "2013.02.16"]
[SourceVersionDate "2014.04.21"]

1. e4 c5 2. Nc3 (2. Nf3 e6 3. d4 cxd4 4. Nxd4 a6 5. Nc3 $6 b5 {this is a
position from the Kan Sicilian, to which White can transpose from our 2.Nc3 a6
move order. It is analyzed below after 3.Nge2} 6. Bd3 {and now both} Qb6 ({
and} 6... Bb7 7. O-O Nc6 8. Nxc6 Bxc6 {give Black good chances})) 2... a6 $1 {
This is the best and most flexible move for a Najdorf player. Don't forget,
White can always transpose to the open Sicilian with a sudden Nf3, d4, or Nge2,
d4 continuation on the very next moves. So we must play typical Najdorf moves
until the moment, when it becomes clear, that it won't be an open Sicilian at
all (like after White goes d3) . THE MOST IMPORTANT THING TO MENTION is that
after 2...a6!? the d4, Qxd4-d2, b3 system IS RULED OUT, AND SO IS THE
GRAND-PRIX ATTACK WITH f4, Bc4/Bb5 etc!!!} 3. g3 $1 {This may as well
transpose to other lines and vise-versa (d3, Nge2, f4) ! We don't really need
to memorize much, it's more important to know plans and ideas.} (3. f4 b5 4.
Nf3 (4. d4 {because he has the white pieces, he can afford such luxuries!} cxd4
5. Qxd4 Nc6 6. Qf2 e6 7. Bd3 Bb7 $132 8. Nf3 Nb4 9. Be3 Nf6 10. h3 Be7 11. O-O
O-O 12. a3 Nxd3 13. cxd3 d6 14. g4 Rc8 15. Rac1 Nd7 16. g5 Nc5 17. Qe2 d5) 4...
Bb7 5. d3 (5. d4 cxd4 6. Nxd4 e6 7. Bd3 Nc6 $1 (7... Qb6 $1) 8. Nxc6 Bxc6) 5...
e6 6. g3 (6. Qe2 Nc6 7. Be3 Qb6 $1 (7... d6 8. g3 Nf6 9. h3 Be7 10. Bg2 O-O 11.
O-O Nd7)) 6... b4 $1 {SOS!!! WHEN WHITE'S PAWN APPEARS ON f4 VERY VERY EARLY,
A VERY GOOD PLAN IS A FAST 1...b4! 2.Na4 d5! White's pawns on e4 and f4 are
only strong here if they stay together. After he is forced to push e5 or take
exd5, White will suffer from the misplaced f4 pawn.} (6... Nf6 $6 7. Bg2 b4 8.
Ne2 d5 9. e5 Nfd7 {is a worse version for Black, as our Knight is now far away
from f5}) 7. Na4 (7. Ne2 d5 $40 8. e5 (8. exd5 Bxd5 (8... exd5 9. Bg2 Nf6 10.
O-O)) 8... Ne7 $1 (8... h5) 9. Bg2 h5 $1 10. O-O Nf5 $15 11. d4 (11. c3 Nc6 (
11... h4 12. g4 h3 13. Bh1 Nh4) 12. d4 Qb6 13. Rf2 (13. Bd2 cxd4) 13... a5)
11... Nc6 $15 12. Bh3 g6) 7... d5 $1 $132 8. exd5 Bxd5) (3. Nge2 $1 b5 $1 (3...
d6 $5 {this lazy but good move will most likely transpose to a Scheveningen
setup (not a Najdorf)} 4. g3 Nf6 5. Bg2 Nc6 6. O-O e6 (6... e5 $2 7. d3 Be7 8.
f4 $14) 7. d4 (7. d3 Be7 8. f4 O-O 9. h3 Nd7 (9... h6 10. g4 Nh7 11. Be3 b5
$132) 10. g4 b5 $132) 7... cxd4 8. Nxd4 Bd7 $132) 4. d4 $1 {INDEED, THIS MOVE
TRANSPOSES TO THE Kan Sicilian, but to a very good version for Black! 1.e4 c5
2.Nf3 e6 3.d4 cxd4 4.Nxd4 a6 5.Nc3?! (5.Bd3!, 5.c4!) 5...b5! with good
counterplay!} (4. g3 Bb7 {transposes to the 3.g3 variation} 5. Bg2 e6 6. O-O {
This is a Closed Sicilian without the fast f4. Our typical setup will be Nf6,
Nc6, d6. Very important - always calculate e5-push by White as our bishop on
b7 is unprotected!} (6. f4 b4 $1 {Our typical idea works again.} 7. Nb1 d5 8.
exd5 (8. e5 Ne7 (8... h5 9. d4 Nc6) 9. d4 Nf5) 8... Bxd5 9. O-O Bxg2 10. Kxg2
Nc6 $15 (10... Nh6)) 6... Nf6 (6... d5 $2 7. exd5 exd5 8. f4 $2 (8. Nf4 Nf6 9.
d4) (8. d4)) 7. d3 (7. e5 Bxg2 8. Kxg2 Ng4) 7... d6 $1 (7... Be7 $4 8. e5 Bxg2
(8... Nd5 9. Nxd5 exd5 10. Nf4 $18) 9. exf6 Bxf1 10. fxe7 Qxe7 11. Qxf1 $18) (
7... Nc6 $2 8. e5) 8. f4 b4 $5 (8... Nc6) 9. Nb1 Nc6 $1 10. Nd2 (10. e5 dxe5
11. fxe5 Nd5 (11... Nd7 {White has many weaknesses})) 10... Be7 $132 11. h3 d5
$36 (11... O-O 12. g4 h6 13. Ng3 Nh7 $36 14. Nf3 a5 {intending a4 with a nice,
unclear position. Our counterplay is on the Queenside and in the centre.}))
4... cxd4 5. Nxd4 e6 $1 {This appears to be better than 5...Bb7, which allows
the annoying 6.Bg5! just like in the game Caruana-Nepomniachtchi.} (5... Bb7 6.
Bg5 $1 $36) 6. Bd3 Qb6 $3 {chasing the knight away from the center just like
in various Najdorf lines!} (6... Bb7) 7. Nb3 (7. Be3 Bc5 8. Be2 Nc6 9. Nxc6
Qxc6 10. Qd2 Ne7 11. a3 Bb7 $132) 7... Qc7 8. O-O Bb7 9. Qe2 Be7 10. Bd2 Nc6
11. f4 d6 12. Rae1 Nf6 $132) (3. Nf3 $6 d6 4. g3 (4. d4 cxd4 5. Nxd4 Nf6 {
and we're back to the Najdorf}) 4... e5 $3 {SOS!!! When we see closed Sicilian
set-ups with Nf3 and without f4, we ALWAYS follow the wise Botvinnik set-up
with Nc6, d6, e5, g6, Bg7, Nge7! And we are ready for a fast f5!} 5. Bg2 Nc6 6.
O-O g6 7. d3 (7. Nd5 Bg7 (7... Nge7 8. Nf6# {maybe you would like to avoid
that...}) 8. c3 Nge7 9. d3 O-O $5 $132 (9... Nxd5 $5 10. exd5 Ne7 11. Nd2 (11.
d4 $6 cxd4 12. cxd4 e4 13. Nd2 f5 $15) 11... O-O 12. a4 b6 $1 $132 (12... f5 $2
{We should not allow the fixing of the queenside of course... Unless we are 100
percent sure we have a very very strong attack on the other side, so we can
ignore it!} 13. a5 Bd7 14. Nc4 Nc8 15. f4 $16) 13. Nc4 Rb8 $132) 10. Bg5 $6 h6
11. Nxe7+ (11. Bf6 $2 Bxf6 12. Nxf6+ Kg7 13. Nd5 Nxd5 14. exd5 Ne7 15. Nd2 b5
$15) 11... Nxe7 12. Be3 f5 $15) 7... Bg7 8. Nd5 Nge7 9. Bg5 h6 $132 10. Bf6
Bxf6 11. Nxf6+ Kf8 $11) (3. Bc4 $2 {This is a very bad try to get a Grand-Prix
Attack. After 2...a6, the Grand Prix is simply ruled out!} e6 $1 4. a4 (4. f4
b5 $17) 4... Nc6 5. f4 Nf6 $3 6. e5 (6. d3 d5) 6... d5 $15 7. Ba2 Ng8 $3 8. Nf3
Nge7 9. O-O h5 10. Ne2 Nf5 $15) (3. d4 $6 cxd4 4. Qxd4 Nc6 5. Qe3 (5. Qd2 $6 e6
6. b3 Nf6 7. Bb2 d5 $1 (7... Bb4 $1 {also simple and good!} 8. Bd3 (8. a3 $4
Nxe4) (8. f3 $6 d5 $1 9. a3 Ba5 10. b4 Bb6 $15 (10... Bc7 $15)) 8... d5 9. exd5
exd5 10. a3 Bd6 (10... Ba5) 11. Nge2 O-O $36) 8. exd5 exd5 9. O-O-O Be6 $15) (
5. Qd3 e6 6. Bf4 b5 $36) (5. Qd1 d6 (5... e6 6. Nf3 b5) 6. Nf3 e5) 5... e6 $132
(5... g6 $132)) (3. a4 Nc6 4. Nf3 e6 5. d4 cxd4 6. Nxd4) 3... b5 4. Bg2 Bb7 5.
d3 e6 (5... e5 $2 {Black is trying for a Botvinnik set-up with e5, Nc6, Nge7,
d6, e5... but this works ONLY when White has played Nf3 without f4. Here,
White has 2 options: either f4 immediately, or Nge2 and f4!, both leading to an
advantage!} 6. Nge2 (6. f4 d6 7. Nf3 $16) 6... d6 7. O-O Nf6 8. f4 $16 {
In fact, if Black had his pawn on e6 here, rather than e5, he would stand very
well! (he would transpose to another line examined here)}) 6. Nge2 (6. f4 {
This appears to be a bit premature!} b4 $1 {SOS!!! ONCE AGAIN WHITE'S PAWN
APPEARS VERY EARLY ON f4 ...AND I STRIKE IMMEDIATELY WITH b5-b4! FOLLOWED BY
d7-d5! AND TAKING BACK ON d5 WITH MY BISHOP!} 7. Nce2 (7. Nb1 d5 $1 8. Nd2 (8.
exd5 Bxd5 $15) (8. e5 Ne7 (8... h5)) 8... Nf6 9. e5 Nfd7 (9... Ng8) 10. Ngf3
Nc6 11. O-O Be7 $15 12. g4 a5 $5 $15 (12... h5 $5)) 7... d5 $1 8. e5 (8. exd5
Bxd5 $1 9. Nf3 Bd6 10. O-O Ne7 $1 $15 11. a3 a5 12. c4 Bc6 13. Be3 Nd7 $15)
8... Ne7 $3 {Black is already better! REMEMBER THIS PLAN WITH Ne7!, h5!, Nf5!}
9. Nf3 h5 10. O-O Nf5 11. d4 (11. c3 Nc6 12. Bd2 (12. d4 Qb6 (12... a5)) 12...
a5 $17) 11... Nc6 $15) 6... d6 7. O-O Nf6 {SOS!!! This is a very good set-up
for black in the g3, Bg2, and f4 lines. But BEFORE I MAKE ANY OF MY MOVES, I
CALCULATE THE e4-e5 advance by White!} 8. h3 (8. e5 $2 Bxg2 9. exf6 Bxf1) (8.
f4 b4 (8... Nc6) 9. Nb1 Nc6) 8... Nc6 $1 {I always play this move to close the
h1-a8 diagonal and avoid any e4-e5 surprises!} (8... Be7 $4 9. e5 $1 $16 {
Now the Be7 is hanging! I wasn't careful of the e4-e5 advance!} Bxg2 (9... Nd5
10. Nxd5 exd5 11. e6 $3 O-O 12. Nf4 $18) 10. exf6 Bxf1 11. fxe7 Qxe7 12. Qxf1
$16) 9. f4 Be7 $132 (9... b4 $5 10. Na4 Be7 11. c3 a5 $1 $132) 10. g4 (10. Be3
O-O 11. a3 Rc8 (11... d5) (11... h6 12. g4 Nh7)) 10... O-O (10... b4 $1 11. Nb1
d5 $15 (11... h6 $132) (11... O-O $5 $132) 12. g5 Nh5) 11. Ng3 (11. Be3 Nd7 12.
d4 cxd4 13. Nxd4) 11... h6 $5 (11... b4) 12. Bd2 (12. g5 hxg5 13. fxg5 Nd7 14.
h4 Nde5 $15) 12... Nh7 $5 $15 {This h6, Nh7 plan is very interesting. On one
hand, it completely stops White's flank attack, on the other hand, this knight
will remain passive on h7 for some time! Nevertheless, Black has a very good
position with nice counterplay in the center and on the queenside!} *

