{[%evp 0,45,15,16,61,38,44,12,9,9,9,11,54,39,26,26,26,-1,4,7,4,-10,-10,-32,-29,
-34,24,13,36,37,65,115,102,129,179,73,128,111,446,464,460,460,460,468,470,399,
424,411]} 1. e4 c5 2. Nf3 (2. c4 Nc6 3. Nf3 e5 {transposes}) (2. f4 d5 $1 (2...
Nc6 3. Bb5 Nd4 {This is playable, but we can't allow White to double our
c-pawns.}) 3. exd5 (3. e5 $2 Nh6 $15 {Great version of the Caro-Kann for Black.
}) 3... Qxd5 4. Nc3 Qd8 5. Nf3 Nc6 6. Bc4 e6 7. O-O Nh6 {with good play for
Black. The white f4-pawn isn't strong when the e-pawn is missing.}) (2. a3 g6
$1 3. b4 Bg7 4. Nc3 d6 $15) (2. b4 $6 cxb4 {We capture the pawn, but we're
ready to offer it back.} 3. a3 (3. d4 d5 4. exd5 Nf6 $15) 3... d5 4. exd5 Qxd5
{White is fighting for equality here.} 5. Nf3 (5. axb4 $4 Qe5+) 5... Bg4 6. Be2
Nc6 7. axb4 Bxf3 8. gxf3 e5 $15) (2. b3 d6 3. Bb2 Nf6 4. Bb5+ Nbd7 5. Qe2 g6 $1
{- see the game Papaioannou-Gelfand}) 2... Nc6 3. c4 e5 $1 {The simplest
set-up against the c4 Sicilian is Nc6, e5!, g6, Bg7 and Nge7, playing for a
fast f5!} 4. Nc3 (4. Be2 g6 5. O-O Bg7 6. d3 Nge7 7. Nc3 O-O 8. Bg5 h6 9. Bxe7
Qxe7 10. Nd5 Qd8 11. a3 d6 12. b4 Kh7 {with chances for both sides}) 4... d6 5.
Be2 g6 6. O-O Bg7 {White's Nf3 makes it harder for him to push the typical
f4-break. Black enjoys a harmonious setup with no problems. For example:} 7.
Nd5 Nge7 8. a3 a5 9. d3 O-O 10. Bg5 f6 11. Bh4 Bd7 $15 *

