{[%evp 0,32,27,20,52,44,48,35,35,7,48,48,66,45,54,10,15,34,13,13,-2,-14,-14,
-14,-14,-14,-6,-27,-32,-45,-37,-37,-21,-19,-27]} 1. e4 c5 2. Nf3 e6 3. d4 cxd4
4. Nxd4 a6 5. Nc3 b5 {One of two big lines. The most common choice is 5...Qc7,
but I like this approach: from now the central e4-pawn feels vulnerable. The
only drawback of such an ambitious choice is a delay in development (at the
moment, none of Black's pieces is developed) .} 6. Be3 {This way of
development can be rarely seen on a high level. In comparison to Taimanov (
where 6.Be3 is currently White's top choice) , the fianchetto makes the e4-pawn
vulnerable. Still, the aggressive setup with Be3, f3, 0-0-0 should be
considered seriously.} Bb7 7. f3 {The most consistent.} ({The other way of
development -} 7. Bd3 Qc7 8. O-O ({After} 8. f4 Nf6 9. Qf3 {the opposition of
Bb7 and Qf3 yields Black various counter-attacking abilities. For instance,}
Nc6 10. O-O-O Nxd4 11. Bxd4 Bc5 12. Bxc5 (12. Bxf6 gxf6 13. Kb1 h5 {is very
good for Black, whose king will stay in the centre.}) 12... Qxc5 13. Qg3 {
Bartel, M - Hambleton, A Biel 2017} Nh5 $1 14. Qg4 g6 15. f5 O-O $11 {Black
will put his queen on e5 soon and fully consolidate.}) 8... Nf6 9. f4 Bc5 {
feels risky for White: both black bishops are very powerful. For instance,} (
9... d6 $5 {also has been tried with success.}) 10. e5 (10. Qf3 d6 11. Qg3 Nbd7
12. Rae1 Qb6 $15 {Ostra,N - Barth,H Dortmund 2019}) 10... Qb6 $1 11. exf6 Bxd4
12. Bxd4 Qxd4+ 13. Kh1 gxf6 {White retains some play for a pawn, but the strong
Bb7 and the open g-file make Black's position look attractive.}) (7. a3 Nf6 8.
f3 {isn't in the spirit of English attack} Qc7 9. Qd2 d5 {I see no reason for
deviating from this thematic break, though Black had some decent alternatives.}
10. exd5 Nxd5 11. Nxd5 Bxd5 12. O-O-O Nc6 13. Nxc6 Qxc6 {The strong Bd5
enabled Black to solve all the problems in Restuccia, F - Sanduay, N Villa
Martelli 2010}) 7... Nf6 8. Qd2 Qc7 {A flexible way of handling the position.}
9. g4 {White can hardly fight for an initiative without this push.} ({In case
of} 9. O-O-O {Black might also diminish the opponent's control of d5 with} b4
10. Na4 ({After} 10. Nce2 e5 $1 11. Nf5 d5 {Black manages to immediately
activate the pieces and obtain an excellent play against White's king. For
instance,} 12. exd5 Nxd5 13. Bg5 $6 Nd7 $17 {Novgorodskij,V - Papin,V Moscow
2008}) 10... d5 {this invites White to enter ''French paths''} 11. e5 Nfd7 ({
Of course, not} 11... Qxe5 $4 12. Bf4 Qh5 13. g4 $18) 12. f4 Nc6 {It is
important, that .. f4-f5 isn't coming so far.} 13. Nb3 Be7 14. Qf2 {White
secures some squares for his awkward Na4} Na5 $1 15. Nb6 ({After} 15. Nbc5 Nxc5
16. Nxc5 Rc8 17. Nxb7 Nxb7 18. Bd3 Nc5 {Black has nothing to worry about.})
15... Nxb3+ 16. axb3 Nxb6 17. Bxb6 Qd7 18. Bd3 a5 $132 {Black had a sufficient
play on the queenside in Milov, L - Poetz, F Bayerisch Eisenstein 2019}) 9...
b4 10. Na4 ({Another natural retreat is} 10. Nce2 h6 $1 11. h4 e5 $1 ({In
comparison to 10.Na4,} 11... d5 $2 {turns out to be a serious mistake:} 12. e5
Nfd7 13. f4 $36 {Black had a poor version of French as White made huge
progress on the kingside.}) 12. Nf5 d5 13. exd5 $2 ({Better was} 13. O-O-O Nbd7
14. Bh3 g6 {, but in this sharp position Black's chances are still preferable.}
) 13... Nxd5 14. Bf2 g6 $17 {0-1 (51) Siwiec,A (2071) -Mihok,O (2351) Guben
2008}) 10... d5 $1 {A well-timed break.} 11. g5 ({Worse is} 11. e5 $6 Nfd7 12.
f4 Nc6 $15 {White was experiencing problems in view of poor Na4 Rigo,J - Papp,T
Hungary 2008}) 11... Nfd7 12. exd5 Bxd5 {White has some development advantage,
but it can be hardly converted - the Bd5 is too strong.} 13. Bg2 Nc6 14. f4 {
This only invites simplifications.} Nxd4 15. Bxd4 Bxg2 16. Qxg2 Rc8 $11 {
Black has successfully solved his problems in Haerig, W - Annaberdiev, M
Karlsruhe 2019} *

