{[%evp 0,42,20,16,48,51,62,46,31,32,81,73,89,55,41,29,29,12,12,12,24,17,17,17,
17,17,2,2,2,-14,0,-17,37,20,53,2,36,36,39,46,40,40,26,27,29]} 1. e4 c5 2. Nf3
e6 3. d4 cxd4 4. Nxd4 a6 5. Nc3 b5 6. g3 Bb7 7. Bg2 Nf6 8. Qe2 {This is the
most challenging deviation from the main line with 8.0-0. White covers the
central pawn and leaves the possibility of ..0-0-0.} (8. Bg5 {This was tried
by a few strong players, including Michael Adams. However, the practice proves
that the pin shouldn't bother Black} Be7 9. O-O b4 10. Na4 Qa5 $1 {Now White
is forced to concess the bishop.} 11. Bxf6 Bxf6 12. c3 O-O {Black managed to
successfully complete his development, and the bishop's pair offered him a
comfortable position. Garcia,G - Gamboa,N Medellin 2000}) (8. a3 $5 {This
prophylactic move isn't as harmless as it looks.} d6 9. O-O Qc7 {A decent move.
Black takes more control of e5 and covers the Bb7.} 10. Re1 {The most natural
and strongest move. From now Black has to do with a standard piece sacrifice on
d5 in various redactions.} ({White achieves no advantage with} 10. f4 Nc6 11.
Be3 Be7 12. Qe2 (12. g4 $6 h5 $1 {White was overextended in Czerniak, M-Kotov,
A Venice 1950}) 12... Nxd4 13. Bxd4 Rc8 $11) ({Too risky seems also} 10. g4 h6
11. f4 Nbd7 {, and now} 12. g5 $6 hxg5 13. fxg5 d5 $1 14. Bf4 Bd6 $36 {leaves
White's king very exposed.}) 10... Nbd7 11. a4 ({Another redaction of the same
idea is} 11. Bg5 $5 Be7 12. a4 bxa4 (12... b4 $6 13. Nd5 exd5 14. exd5 {
is more dangerous for Black.}) 13. Nd5 ({After} 13. Rxa4 O-O 14. Nb3 Nb6 {
Black's knight reaches c4 and puts strong pressure on White's queenside.})
13... exd5 14. exd5 {This was successfully tried twice by GM Leniart. Here I
can suggest an improvement over Black's play:} h6 $5 $146 15. Bxf6 gxf6 16. Nf5
Ne5 {Letting White to regain the piece. On the other hand, it significantly
improves the pawn structure.} 17. Nxe7 Kxe7 18. f4 Bc8 {The Bb7 already did its
job.} 19. fxe5 fxe5 20. Rxa4 Bd7 {The Ke7 feels safe in the centre, so Black
should be OK.}) 11... b4 12. Na2 ({The more aggressive} 12. Nd5 exd5 13. exd5+
{is well met by} Ne5 $1 (13... Kd8 $2 14. Nc6+ Bxc6 15. dxc6 $18 {Quintiliano
Pinto,R - De Oliveira,A Cuiaba 2021}) 14. f4 O-O-O $1 15. fxe5 dxe5 {Black
takes over the initiative.}) 12... Nc5 13. Nxb4 ({Possible is also} 13. c3 b3
14. Nxb3 Ncxe4 $132) 13... Ncxe4 14. Bf4 {This position occurred in Danielyan,
V - Pantsulaia, L Tbilisi 2017 In my opinion, White's last move should be
naturally met by} e5 15. Qd3 Nc5 16. Qf5 Bxg2 17. Kxg2 Be7 $132 {Black is
close to completing development when his pawn structure is superior.}) 8... b4
9. Na4 {The Na4 is misplaced, but it can be defended easily with b2-b3.} ({
Too passive is} 9. Nb1 $6 Nc6 10. Be3 Qc7 $15 {Aleksic,N - Razuvaev, Y Cutro
2000}) 9... Qa5 10. b3 Nc6 11. Bb2 ({has no independent value, as Black cat at
least play} 11. Be3 Nxd4 {with a transposition.} (11... Rc8 $5) 12. Bxd4) 11...
Nxd4 12. Bxd4 {White is leading in the development, so Black should be very
accurate form now.} e5 $1 {It is a good moment for fixing the pawn structure
and eliminating the possibility of ..e4-e5.} 13. Bb6 ({After} 13. Be3 Nxe4 14.
Nb6 {the activity of pieces offers White a definite compensation for the
central pawn, but hardly it suffices for more than equality. For instance,} Rd8
15. Nc4 Qb5 16. Bd4 {This was Gantar,J - Lochte,S Reykjavik 2019 Now I mostly
like} f6 $146 17. Bxe5 (17. Bxe4 $2 Bxe4 18. Qxe4 d5 $17) 17... d5 $1 18. Bd4
Be7 {There is no way White can keep the queens on the board.} 19. Ne3 Qxe2+ 20.
Kxe2 Kf7 21. Rhd1 Rc8 {The pawns c2 and d5 are equally weak, so Black is fine.}
) ({The other retreat -} 13. Bb2 {looks less attractive for White:} Bc6 14. f4
(14. Qe3 Bxa4 15. bxa4 Bc5 $15) 14... d6 $1 {Now, most of White's minor pieces
look ugly} 15. O-O-O ({Bad is} 15. O-O $2 {Sahoo, U - Fominyh, A Kolkata 2012}
Bb5 16. Qd2 Bxf1 17. Rxf1 Be7 $17) 15... Bxa4 16. bxa4 Be7 {Black has the
better pawn structure, while the bishops pair isn't effective enough.}) 13...
Qb5 {Now White should either trade queens or waste a tempo by moving his queen.
} 14. Qd3 ({After} 14. Qe3 Be7 15. O-O-O O-O 16. Rhe1 Qc6 17. Kb1 a5 {Black
took over the initiative in Novoselski, Z - Eisenbeiser, A Boeblingen 2013}) (
14. Qxb5 axb5 15. Nc5 Bxc5 16. Bxc5 Bxe4 17. Bxe4 Nxe4 18. Bxb4 d5 {was equal
in Horvath,Z - Markus,R Hungary 2013}) 14... Be7 15. O-O-O {We have been
following the game Petrosian, T - Koneru, H Cochin 2004 At this point I offer
the following new idea:} Rb8 $146 {Black is trying to take advantage of
unstable Bb6} 16. f4 ({The bishop's manoeuvre:} 16. Ba7 Ra8 17. Be3 Ng4 18. Bb6
{should be energetically met by} f5 $1 19. Rhe1 (19. Qd2 Nf6 $132) 19... Qxd3
20. Rxd3 Bc6 {with a decent counterplay.}) 16... Qxd3 17. Rxd3 exf4 18. Bc7 Rc8
19. Bxf4 Bxe4 20. Bxe4 Nxe4 21. Re1 f5 *

