{[%evp 0,30,26,15,44,44,44,25,25,25,77,77,83,58,74,57,68,55,63,40,52,38,26,34,
40,22,39,21,19,5,9,8,-4]} 1. e4 c5 2. Nf3 e6 3. d4 cxd4 4. Nxd4 a6 5. Nc3 b5 6.
Bd3 {Undoubtedly, this is the most challenging move: White takes care of
central pawn and goes for a quick kingside castle.} Bb7 7. O-O ({The other
natural move is} 7. Qe2 {It yields White some tactical ideas with ..Nc3-d5 and
also leaves the option of queenside castle actual.} Ne7 $5 {I like this
flexible move: Black might consider both placing the knight on g6 and also
after ... Nbc6 it is possible to recapture with the king's knight.} ({Instead,
the common} 7... Nc6 8. Nxc6 Bxc6 9. a4 b4 10. Nd5 $36 {feels a bit
uncomfortable for Black in view of undeveloped kingside pieces.}) 8. Be3 {
I find this move the most consistent - after ..0-0-0 White will reach a decent
attacking setup.} (8. O-O Nbc6 9. Nxc6 ({After} 9. Nb3 Ng6 10. f4 Be7 11. Be3
Nb4 {Black magaed to liquidate the strong Bd3 and obtain a comfortable
position in Granovskiy,A - Dvalishvili,P Moscow 2013}) 9... Bxc6 {transposes
to the main line.}) 8... Nec6 $1 {A clever response - Black has to unlock the
dark-squared bishop as soon as it possible.} 9. O-O-O Nxd4 10. Bxd4 Nc6 11. Be3
Qa5 12. Kb1 {The natural play by both sides led to this position in Beerdsen,T
- Indjic,A Chess.com INT 2020 My new natural idea now is} Be7 $1 $146 13. Qh5
O-O 14. f4 Rac8 $132 {Black's attacking chances are by no meas worse.}) (7. Be3
Nc6 8. Nxc6 Bxc6 9. Qe2 {, as in Meszaros,T - Balogh,C Ajka 2020 can be well
met by} b4 $1 10. Nb1 Nf6 11. Nd2 {White wasted few tempi for moving his
knights, and after} Be7 12. O-O-O Qc7 13. f4 a5 $132 {Black has a great play
on the queenside.}) 7... Nc6 8. Nxc6 ({In case of} 8. Be3 Ne5 $1 9. f4 Nxd3 10.
cxd3 Nf6 $132 {White hardly can take advantage of his better development as
after ..e4-e5 Black's unopposed light-squared bishop will become too strong.})
8... Bxc6 9. Re1 (9. Qe2 {was also played times by strong players.} Be7 {
This is my preference. By making this move Black eliminates the standard
tactical idea ..Nc3-d5 and makes Ng8-f6 viable. I was actually surprised, that
it was only seen twice in a tournament practice so far.} ({The other
considerable options are:} 9... Bc5 $5) ({and} 9... Ne7 $5) 10. a3 $146 {
This is already a new move. I find it important to stop...b5-b4.} (10. Bf4 {
is what White played in both games and after} b4 11. Nb1 Nf6 12. Nd2 O-O {
Black completes his development and shouldn't face any problems.}) (10. a4 b4)
({The more ambitious} 10. f4 {is also met by} b4 11. Nd1 Nf6 {,and now} 12. e5
Nd5 13. f5 exf5 14. Rxf5 O-O $132 {doesn't offer White a real attack, while
his own king isn't that safe.}) 10... Qc7 11. Re1 h5 $5 {This somewhat
provocative move is typical for Kan: Black leaves his king in the centre (at
least temporarily) , but from now White should deal with such
counter-attacking ideas as ...h5-h4-h3 and Nf6-g4.} ({Instead,} 11... Nf6 12.
e5 Nd5 13. Nxd5 Bxd5 14. Qg4 {puts Black's king under some pressure.}) 12. Bd2
Nf6 13. e5 Ng4 $132) ({The ambitious} 9. e5 {feels too early and can be
strongly met by} f5 $1 10. exf6 Nxf6 11. Qe2 Be7 12. Bf4 O-O {Black had an
excellent piece play in Schmidek, E - Kamsky, G Karlsruhe 2019}) ({The other
developing move} 9. Be3 {allows} b4 $1 10. Ne2 Nf6 11. f3 Qc7 {Black reaches a
harmonious setup and after} 12. Qe1 d5 {it is White who has to take care of
equality.}) 9... Ne7 $5 ({The somewhat more natural way of development is} 9...
Bc5 {, but after} 10. Qh5 $1 Qb6 11. Be3 Bxe3 12. Rxe3 Ne7 13. Nd5 $1 {White
has a great attacking setup.}) 10. Bg5 ({The attempt to claim the drawbacks of
early b7-b5 with} 10. a4 b4 11. Ne2 {isn't so dangerous, as Black is in time
to regroup his forces} Ng6 12. Nd4 Bb7 13. Qh5 Qc7 {Black was doing well and
after} 14. e5 $6 Bc5 15. Nb3 Ba7 $15 {White found himself overextended in
Krejci, J - Zueger, B Merlimont 2011}) ({The immediate} 10. Qh5 Ng6 11. a4 {
allows} Bb4 $1 ({But not} 11... b4 $6 12. Nd5 $36) 12. axb5 (12. Bd2 $6 bxa4
$15 {Benderac,S - Miladinovic,I Montenegro 2016}) 12... axb5 13. Bd2 Rxa1 14.
Rxa1 Qb8 $132 {Nothing can prevent Black from castling, so he is OK.}) ({
The same pin effectively works after} 10. Be3 Ng6 11. a4 Bb4 $1 {For instance,}
12. axb5 axb5 13. Rxa8 Qxa8 {, and now the only challenging way is} 14. Nxb5
Bxb5 15. Bxb5 Bxe1 16. Bxd7+ Kf8 17. Qxe1 Kg8 18. Bb5 Qxe4 {This was Fritsche,F
- Tosi, F ICCF email 2010. The queenside passers provide White with full
compensation for an exchange, but with such a safe king Black shouldn't be in
trouble.}) ({The modest} 10. Bd2 Ng6 11. a4 {should be met by} bxa4 $1 $146 ({
Bad is} 11... b4 $6 12. Nd5 a5 13. c3 $36 {Riff,J - Zueger,B Switzerland 2012})
12. Nxa4 Bd6 13. Be3 Bc7 {The active piece playfully compensates for the weak
a6-pawn.}) 10... Qb8 {The Qb8 cannot be attacked, and Black takes control of
the b8-h2 diagonal.} (10... Qc7 $5 {is perfectly playable either.}) 11. a4 (11.
e5 $6 {, as in Panarin,M - Kamsky,G Sochi 2015 runs into} b4 $1 12. Ne4 Ng6 $15
{White struggles to defend the central pawn.}) 11... b4 12. Ne2 Ng6 13. Nd4 {
This position occurred in Felgaer, R - Bachmann, A Asuncion 2011 In my opinion,
Black could have played} Bb7 $5 $146 14. Qd2 Bd6 15. Nf3 O-O {All the problems
are solved.} *

