[TimeControl "180"]

1. e4 c5 2. Nf3 d6 3. d4 cxd4 4. Qxd4 Nc6 5. Bb5 {is the most challenging and
most played move.} (5. Qe3 {is somewhat fashionable lately, but is not really
a big deal. Although this move and other queen moves are not critical, you
can't expect to gain an advantage. Instead, there will be a normal and equal
position and you should just play chess! This is actually White's goal: to
avoid heavy theory while both players have chances. In this particular line,
Black has two options.} Bg4 $1 {[%cal Gg4f3] Eventually Black will take the
f3-Knight.} (5... g6 $1 {[%cal Gf8g7] is also simple and good. Note that Bf8-h6
is not a threat due to Qe3-c3.} 6. Bc4 Bg7 7. Nc3 Nf6 8. O-O (8. Bd2 $6 {
[%cal Ge1c1] is a bit too much.} O-O 9. O-O-O Bd7 $15 {with a very good
version of the Dragon, White has played too many unnatural moves.}) 8... O-O {
[%cal Gc8g4]} 9. h3 {[%cal Yh3g4,Rc8g4]} b6 $1 {[%cal Gc8b7] The c8-bishop
will sit nicely on b7.} (9... a6 {is also possible.} 10. a4 Bd7 $132) 10. Rd1
Qc7 $1 11. Nd5 (11. Nb5 Qb8 $11) 11... Nxd5 12. exd5 Na5 13. Bd3 Bb7 $15) 6. c4
g6 7. Nc3 Bg7 8. Be2 Nf6 9. O-O Bxf3 10. Bxf3 Nd7 11. Rd1 O-O $11 {We have
reached an interesting version of the Maroczy. This is a good time to once
more stress that against these random queen moves on move five, we're happy to
have a playable position and should not expect anything special. This is
exactly the case here.}) 5... Bd7 6. Bxc6 (6. Qd3 $5 {This is an interesting
alternative and will probably grow in popularity. Black has several options.}
Rc8 $1 (6... Nf6 $1 7. c4 Ne5 $1 {After the exchanges, White has a better pawn
structure, but also a weak d4-square and a weak c4-pawn in many lines!} 8. Nxe5
dxe5 9. Nc3 (9. Bxd7+ Qxd7 10. Qxd7+ Nxd7 11. Nc3 e6 {Black has good
counterplay, let's check some sample lines.} 12. Ke2 (12. Nb5 Rc8 $17 {[%csl
Rc4][%cal Yc8c4,Ga7a6]}) (12. Be3 Bc5 13. Bxc5 Nxc5 14. Ke2 a5 15. Rhd1 Ke7 16.
b3 g5 $132) 12... Rc8 13. b3 Bc5 14. Rd1 f6 15. Bd2 g5 $132 (15... Ke7 $132)) (
9. Qe2 e6 10. O-O Bxb5 11. cxb5 Bc5 12. Rd1 Qb6 13. a4 O-O 14. Bd2 Rfd8 15. Nc3
Bd4 16. Be1 Rac8 $15) 9... a6 10. Bxd7+ Qxd7 11. Qxd7+ Nxd7 12. Ke2 e6 13. Bd2
(13. Be3 Rc8 $11) 13... Rc8 14. b3 Ba3 (14... Bc5 $5) 15. Rab1 Ke7 $132 16.
Rhd1 Rc6 17. f3 Rhc8 $11 {1/2-1/2 Nepomniachtchi,I-Gelfand,B/Sochi 2014/EXT
2015}) 7. c4 (7. O-O $4 Nb4 $17) (7. Bd2 Nf6 8. c4 Ne5 $1 9. Nxe5 dxe5 10.
Bxd7+ $6 (10. Nc3 e6 11. Rd1 (11. O-O $4 Bxb5 $19 {and all of a sudden Black
wins a piece.}) 11... a6 12. Bxd7+ Qxd7 13. Qxd7+ Nxd7 14. b3 Bc5 $132) 10...
Qxd7 11. Qxd7+ Kxd7 $1 12. f3 Rxc4 $15 {and only Black has winning chances
with the extra pawn.}) 7... Nb4 $1 8. Bxd7+ Qxd7 9. Qb3 (9. Qe2 g6 10. O-O Bg7
11. a3 Nc6 12. Rd1 Qe6 $5 13. Nbd2 (13. Nc3 $2 Bxc3 14. bxc3 Nf6 $15) 13... Nf6
14. h3 O-O $15) (9. Qc3 Nc6 10. O-O Nf6 11. Re1 g6 (11... e6 $5 $132) 12. b3
Bg7 13. Bb2 O-O $132) 9... Nc6 10. Nc3 g6 (10... Na5 $5 11. Qa3 Nxc4 12. Qxa7
g6 13. Qd4 Nf6 $132) 11. O-O Bg7 12. Be3 (12. Qc2 Nb4 $5 (12... Nf6 $132) 13.
Qe2 Qc7 $3 14. a3 Na6 15. Nb5 Qxc4 $15) 12... Nf6 (12... Na5 13. Qb4 b6 $132)
13. Rad1 Ng4 $132) 6... Bxc6 {Here White has three ways to continue. The main
line is 7.Nc3, while 7.c4 aiming for a Maroczy and 7.Bg5 trying to stop 7...
Nf6 is the alternatives.} 7. Nc3 (7. Bg5 $2 {This move appears to be clever as
we are not in time to play ...h6 and it's not possible to play ...Ng8-Nf6
without getting captured on f6! Nevertheless, it hits on a tremendous
refutation!} f6 $3 8. Be3 (8. Bh4 e5 9. Qe3 h5 $3 $17 {is an amazing move
found by Stockfish. We are threatening to trap the h4-bishop forcing White to
break the pin.} (9... d5 {make sure you don't blunder this!} 10. Nxe5 $16) 10.
h3 Qb6 $3 11. Qxb6 axb6 12. Nc3 g5 13. Bg3 h4 14. Bh2 b5 $17 {[%csl Gc6,Gf8]})
8... e5 $1 $15 9. Qc4 d5 10. exd5 Qxd5 11. Qxd5 Bxd5 12. Nc3 Bc6 $1 {[%csl Gc6,
Gf8] The pair of bishops secures an advantage.} 13. O-O-O Ne7 14. Bc5 {White
tries to make sure Black has to give up the bishop pair. Here 14...Ne7-f5 and
14...Ke8-f7 gives Black the upper hand, but even 14...g7-g6 is enough to be
better. Check out the model games section for further analyses.} Nf5 $5 $15 {
0-1 (50) Bierenbroodspot,P-Nijboer,F/Netherlands 2009/EXT 2010} (14... Kf7 $5
15. Rhe1 Nd5 $3 $17 (15... Ng6 16. Bxf8 Rhxf8 $15) 16. Ne4 Bxc5 17. Nxc5 Nf4
$17)) (7. c4 {White wants to set up the Maroczy bind, but Black is ready to
prevent that with the coffeehouse chess like 7...f7-f5!} f5 $1 8. exf5 (8. Nc3
fxe4 $5 9. Nxe4 Nf6 10. Nxf6+ $2 gxf6 11. Qg4 e5 $3 12. Qh5+ Kd7 $17 {[%csl
Gc6][%cal Gh8g8,Gd7c7] Black is much better after this weird-looking line due
to the strong light-squared bishop. The Black king can find safety on the
c7-square. Whites king on the other won't be comfortable after Rh8-g8.}) 8...
Qa5+ 9. Nbd2 Qxf5 10. O-O e5 {[%csl Rd2,Rf3][%cal Rf3d5,Rd2d5] and Black has
an excellent position. The main problem for White is that the knights are far
away from the important d5-square. After finishing development Black will enjoy
life.} 11. Qe3 Be7 {[%cal Rf3d4,Gg8f6,Ge8g8] blocking the pin.} (11... Nf6 $2 {
Allowing White to claim the advantage as illustrated in the following game:}
12. Nd4 Qh5 13. Nxc6 bxc6 14. Ne4 $16 {½-½ Vokarev, S (2455) -Sjugirov, S (2643
) RUS-chT 18th Olginka 2011 (6)}) 12. b4 (12. c5 O-O-O $11 {0-1 (16)
Wen,Y-Popov,V/St Petersburg 2009/CBM 132 Extra}) 12... Nf6 13. b5 Bxf3 14. Nxf3
O-O $11 {1/2 (26) -1/2 Jovanovic, Z-Bologan, V/Neum 2008/CBM 124 Extra}) 7...
h6 $1 {This is a very good and typical move. We want to stop Bc1-g5xf6 ideas (
after we have played ...e7-e5) . This way the c1-bishop is not active! The
position very much resembles the Bb5+ Sicilian after the moves: 1.e4-c5 2.
Nf3-d6 3.Bb5+-Nd7 4. d4-cxd4 5.Qxd4-a6 6.Bxd7+-Bxd7 7.Nc3-e5! 8.Qd3-h6!!. We
start with ...h7-h6 first because in some cases we don't have to play ...e7-e5,
so this way is more flexible. The advantage of this line compared to the more
often played 7...Nf6 lays in the complexity: White's moves are very easy and
natural in the main line, while here this is the case for Black!} 8. Be3 (8.
Nd2 $6 Nf6 9. Nc4 g6 $17 10. Ne3 Bg7 11. Qd3 O-O 12. O-O Nd7 13. Ned5 Nc5 {
0-1 (69) Kacharava,N-Banikas,H/followchess.com 2020/[,ÃéÜííçò]}) (8. Qd3 {
[%cal Gf3d4]} e5 {it's important to stop Nf3-d4. Now most moves will transpose.
} 9. Nd5 {is premature.} Nf6 $15 (9... Bxd5 {is also possible, though not
necessary.} 10. Qxd5 (10. exd5 Nf6 11. O-O Be7 $11 {[%cal Ge8g8, Gf6d7,Gf7f5]
with a very nice Najdorf type of position.}) 10... Qc7 11. O-O Nf6 12. Qd3 Rc8
13. c3 Be7 $11 {[%cal Ge8g8]})) (8. O-O e5 9. Qd3 Nf6 {[%cal Gf8e7, Ge8g8] Our
plan is very simple: we bring our king to safety with ...Bf8-e7 and short
castle. Then we play on the queenside with ...b7-b5 or we play ...d6-d5 when
given the chance. White's dark-squared bishop is problematic in these lines.
It's not really important to know the theory here, we'll continue with some
sample lines to understand the concepts in this position.} 10. Nd2 {[%cal
Gd2c4,Gc4e3]} (10. Be3 {[%csl Re3] is not a good move in combination with the
short castle. White needs the e3-square for the f3-knight to try to control the
d5-square.} Be7 {Please don't play Nf6-g4 with the idea to capture the
e3-bishop. Remeber why we played ...h7-h6 in the first place: to stop this
exchange.} 11. Rfe1 O-O 12. Rad1 {Black is already better, we'll check some
moves to understand the different ideas.} Qc7 $15 {[%cal Gf8d8,Ga8c8] is what
would be considered the normal move. After some Nc3-d5 (at the moment this is
not possible due to ...Bc6xd5 followed by ...e5-e4 winning a piece) we can
take with the f6-knight freeing the f-pawn to advance to the f5-square.} (12...
Qc8 $15 {[%cal Gc8e6] The queen can go to the e6-square from where it has good
central control.}) (12... b5 $15 {is a move we want to play anyway} 13. a3 {
and here we can continue with 13...a7-a5 or the more quiet 13...a7-a6.} a5 $15
(13... a6 $15))) (10. Rd1 $5 Be7 11. Nh4 g6 $1 {This is how they react against
the Nf3-h4 jumps. If for some tactical reason ...g7-g6 does not work, ...
Bc6-d7 is a fine alternative.} 12. Nf3 Kf8 $1 (12... b5 $1 13. a3 Kf8 14. Nd2
Qb6 15. Nf1 Qb7 16. f3 Kg7 $132) 13. a4 Kg7 $132 {1-0 (142) Paichadze,
L-Antipov,M/Izmir TUR 2016/[,ÃéÜííçò]}) 10... d5 $3 $36 {REMEMBER THIS IDEA!
This is the exception where you should know the move by heart!} 11. exd5 (11.
Qg3 Qc7 12. Re1 O-O-O $15) 11... Nxd5 12. Re1 (12. Nc4 Nxc3 13. Qxc3 f6 $1 14.
Be3 Qd5 15. f3 Bb5 $1 $15 (15... Rc8 $132) (15... Qe6 16. Rfd1 (16. Rad1 Bb5)
16... Rc8 $15)) 12... Nxc3 $3 13. Rxe5+ (13. Qxc3 f6 14. f4 (14. Nc4 Qd5 15.
Ne3 Qe6) 14... Qb6+) 13... Be7 14. Qxc3 O-O $17 15. Re1 Bf6 {With a huge lead
in development and a very strong pair of bishops on an open board, only
engines can hold this position for White. The extra pawn for White won't play
a role for many moves to come.} 16. Qg3 (16. Qd3 Qa5 17. Rf1 Rad8 18. Nb3 Qh5
$19) 16... Qa5 $17) 8... e5 $5 9. Qd3 (9. Qc4 Nf6 10. O-O-O {[%cal Yd1d8,Yf3e5]
} Qc8 $1 $11 {[%cal Gc8e6,Gb7b5]}) 9... Nf6 10. O-O-O Be7 {another basic
position of this system...but a very good one for black! Let's check some
possible lines} 11. Nh4 $1 {possibly the only good move for white here} (11.
Rhg1 $6 Qd7 $1 $15 12. Nh4 (12. h3 b5 $17 13. Nd2 Qb7 $17 {[%csl Re4][%cal
Yb7e4,Yb7b2]}) (12. g4 Nxg4 13. h3 Nxe3 14. Qxe3 Bf6 $17 (14... Qxh3 $5 $17 15.
Rxg7 Qe6 16. Nd5 Bxd5 17. Rxd5 h5 18. Rg1 h4 {0-1 (37) Du, Y-Ding Yixin/China
CHN 2016})) 12... g6 13. g3 Ng4 14. Nf3 Rc8 15. Kb1 b5 16. Rge1 a6 {1/2 (57)
-1/ 2 Ding, Y-Ju, W/Xinghua 2012/CBM 147 Extra}) (11. Kb1 $6 O-O 12. g4 Nxg4
13. Rhg1 Qd7 $17 (13... f5 $17)) (11. h3 b5 $1 $36 (11... Qd7 12. Kb1 b5 13.
Nd2 Qb7 14. f4 O-O 15. fxe5 dxe5 16. Nf3 b4 17. Ne2 Bb5 {0-1 Lopez Hernandez,
C-Dobrov,V/Neiva 2005/CBM 106 ext}) 12. Nxb5 Nxe4 13. Nxa7 Rxa7 $3 14. Bxa7 O-O
15. Be3 Qa8 16. a3 Rc8 $17 17. Kb1 Ba4 $17 (17... Rb8 $17)) (11. Rhe1 $6 {
is pointless} O-O $15 12. g3 b5 13. Nh4 b4 {0-1 (53) Posta,P-Novotny,J/Czechia
2002/EXT 2007}) 11... g6 $1 12. Rhf1 Rc8 $1 (12... Ng4 13. Nf3 Qa5 $132) 13. f4
O-O 14. fxe5 Ng4 15. Nf3 dxe5 $132 *

