1. e4 c5 2. Nf3 Nc6 3. Bb5 d6 4. d4 cxd4 5. Qxd4 {Through a different move
order we reach the position we know.} Bd7 6. Bxc6 Bxc6 7. Bg5 $2 f6 $3 8. Be3
e5 9. Qc4 d5 $15 10. exd5 Qxd5 $1 {It is smart to take back with the queen.
Our advantage exists because of the pair of bishops, while our position might
be slightly weakened with the pawn on the f6-square, especially with queens on
the board. In the endgame, our bishops will be powerful and the weakness is not
important.} 11. Qxd5 Bxd5 12. Nc3 Bc6 13. O-O-O Ne7 14. Bc5 {Because White has
some advantage in development, it might be necessary for Black to give back
the bishop pair.} Nf5 (14... Ng6 $5) 15. Bxf8 Rxf8 16. Rd2 g5 (16... Rd8 $5)
17. Nd5 g4 18. Ne1 O-O-O 19. Ne3 Rxd2 20. Kxd2 Rd8+ 21. Kc1 Nxe3 22. fxe3 {
and this endgame is already winning for Black according to the computers.} Kd7
$3 {is a typical grandmaster move. We temporarily block the d-file to activate
the king and also protect the f6-pawn.} 23. Rf1 Ke6 24. Rf2 g3 (24... h5 $5 {
is maybe better.}) 25. hxg3 Rg8 26. Kd2 Rxg3 27. Ke2 h5 28. Nf3 Be4 29. c4 a5
30. b3 Rg4 31. Kf1 h4 32. Nd2 Bc6 33. Nf3 a4 34. Ne1 Rg3 35. Ke2 Be4 36. Nf3
Rg4 37. Kd2 f5 38. Kc3 axb3 39. axb3 h3 40. gxh3 Rg3 41. Nd2 Rxe3+ 42. Kb4 Rxh3
43. Nxe4 fxe4 44. Re2 Kf5 45. Rf2+ Rf3 46. Rg2 Rd3 47. Rf2+ Ke6 48. Re2 e3 49.
Ka3 e4 50. Re1 Ke5 0-1

