1. e4 c5 2. Nf3 d6 3. d4 cxd4 4. Qxd4 Nc6 5. Bb5 Bd7 6. Bxc6 Bxc6 7. Bg5 f6 8.
Be3 e5 9. Qd3 d5 10. exd5 Qxd5 11. Qxd5 Bxd5 12. Nc3 Bc6 13. O-O-O Ne7 14. Rhe1
g6 15. Bc5 Bh6+ {and Black keeps the pair of bishops for the moment, in this
game he kept them forever.} 16. Kb1 Kf7 17. Bxe7 Kxe7 18. Nd5+ Kf7 19. c4 Rad8
20. b3 Rd7 {[%cal Gh8d8] Black starts to double the rooks.} 21. a4 Rhd8 22. Nc3
Rxd1+ 23. Rxd1 Rxd1+ 24. Nxd1 Bg7 $1 {preparing ...f7-f5 followed by ...e5-e4
without White allowing to answer with Nf3-d4.} 25. Ne1 f5 26. Kc2 Ke6 27. Nc3
h5 28. b4 b6 29. g3 (29. a5 bxa5 {is instructive, being a pawn up is a good
thing, White will need to spend too much time to regain it. White's passed
pawn is not an issue.} (29... Bf8 $6 {is the safer option, but allows White to
exchange a couple of pawns and reduce Black's winning chances.}) 30. b5 Be8 31.
c5 Bf8 32. c6 Bc5 $19) 29... g5 30. b5 Bb7 31. Nd3 e4 32. Nb4 Bd4 33. Nd1 f4
34. Kd2 Bc5 35. Kc3 Ke5 36. Nc2 h4 37. Kd2 hxg3 38. hxg3 Bc8 39. gxf4+ gxf4 40.
Ke1 Be6 41. Nb2 Bf5 42. Kd2 Bd4 43. Nd1 Be6 44. Nb4 Bxc4 45. Nc6+ Kd5 46. Nxa7
Bb3 47. Nc8 Bxa4 48. Nxb6+ Bxb6 49. Nc3+ Kc4 50. Nxa4 Ba5+ 51. Ke2 Kxb5 52.
Nc3+ Bxc3 0-1

