1. e4 c5 2. Nf3 d6 3. d4 cxd4 4. Qxd4 Nc6 5. Bb5 Bd7 6. Bxc6 Bxc6 7. Nc3 e5 8.
Qd3 h6 9. O-O Nf6 10. Nd2 d5 11. exd5 Nxd5 12. Nc4 Nxc3 13. Qxc3 f6 {
Everything is protected and we still have the pair of bishops. Some caution is
needed because our king is still stuck in the middle of the board.} 14. Be3 Qd5
$1 15. f3 Be7 (15... Bb5 $1 {This was the best move, intending to give back
the bishop pair, destroying White's pawn structure in the process.} 16. b3 Bxc4
17. bxc4 Qc6 {and now for example:} 18. Rfd1 $2 (18. Qd3 Kf7 19. Qd5+ Qxd5 20.
cxd5 Bd6 {[%csl Gf7] With the more active king only Black can be better.} 21.
c4 Rhc8 22. Rfc1 Ba3 23. Rc2 Bc5 $15) 18... Bc5 19. Bxc5 Qxc5+ 20. Kh1 Rc8 21.
Qd3 O-O 22. Qd5+ Qxd5 23. cxd5 Rxc2 $17) (15... Rc8 $5 {is also interesting.}
16. Rfd1 Qe6 17. Qd3 Be7 (17... Kf7 18. Bxa7 e4 $11) 18. Nd6+ Bxd6 19. Qxd6
Qxd6 20. Rxd6 Ke7 21. Rad1 (21. Bc5 Bxf3 $3 22. Ba3 Bh5 $15) 21... b6 $132) 16.
Rfd1 Qe6 17. Na5 {and White takes away the bishop pair under favourable
circumstances.} Bd5 (17... O-O) (17... Kf7 {[%csl Gf7]} 18. Nxc6 bxc6 $14) 18.
Qd3 Rd8 19. c4 Qa6 20. cxd5 Qxa5 21. Qg6+ Kf8 22. Rac1 Bd6 23. a3 b6 24. Rc6
Qa6 25. Rdc1 Qb7 26. a4 Re8 27. a5 bxa5 28. Bc5 Bxc5+ 29. R1xc5 Qf7 30. Qf5 g6
31. Qg4 Rh7 32. Rc8 Rxc8 33. Rxc8+ Kg7 1-0

