{In this lecture we will cover the Delayed alapin Sicilian & some sidelines. As
always, our aim is to find lines that give us easier play with a lot of
chances to fight for the win.} 1. e4 c5 2. Nf3 d6 3. d4 (3. c3 {The start of
the delayed alapin variation.} Nf6 {Our main approach.}) (3. Bc4 {This is very
similar to the delayed alapin and often transposes into the same. We will
respond in the same way.} Nf6) 3... cxd4 4. Nxd4 Nf6 5. f3 {This is not
exactly a Najdorf but not an Open Sicilian as well. It is kind of something
between them. White aims to of course push c4 and establish a maroczy bind.} e5
6. Nb3 a5 {many other options are playable but this gives the best attacking
chances.} *

[Event "Salamanca"]
[Site "Salamanca"]
[Date "1988.??.??"]
[Round "?"]
[White "Delayed Alapin & 3.Bc4"]
[Black "Theoretical Overview"]
[Result "*"]
[ECO "B50"]
[Annotator "GM Ioannis Papaioannou"]
[PlyCount "24"]
[EventDate "1988.??.??"]
[EventType "tourn"]
[EventRounds "11"]
[EventCountry "ESP"]
[EventCategory "7"]
[SourceVersionDate "2014.04.21"]

1. e4 c5 2. Nf3 d6 3. c3 {The Delayed Alapin variation. White simply wants to
take the center with d4.} (3. Bc4 $5 {This is similar to the delayed c3
Sicilian. We should better play a fast 3...Nf6, to avoid this 0-0 -Re1 lines !}
Nf6 $1 (3... Nc6 $6 {This is not recommended.} 4. O-O Nf6 5. Re1 $1 {White
will manage to play d4 later on.}) 4. d3 (4. e5 $6 {is a bit premature.} dxe5
5. Nxe5 e6 6. Qe2 a6 7. a4 Bd6 {We are fine! White has wasted too many moves
trying to 'win quickly' and he will pay the price later on.}) 4... Nc6 5. c3 a6
$3 {a very sophisticated move order! We are planning Na5 next.} (5... Bg4 $4 {
lose a pawn to} 6. Qb3) 6. Bb3 (6. a4 {stopping b5, but we have something else
in our mind as well!} Bg4 $1 7. Qb3 $2 e6 8. Qxb7 Na5 {The major difference is
that White's queen is now trapped as the b5-square is controlled by the small
pawn on a6.}) 6... Bg4 7. Nbd2 e6 8. h3 Bh5 9. O-O Be7 10. Re1 O-O 11. Nf1 h6
$3 $15 {Our play follows just like in the mainline of delayed alapin.}) 3...
Nf6 {Stopping d4. We are obviously not intending to take on e4 as it falls to
Qa4.} 4. Be2 $1 (4. Bd3 $5 {White is planning Bc2 & d4.} Bg4 $3 {the most
accurate! plan. Planning Nc6 to stop d4 plans.} 5. h3 Bh5 6. O-O (6. Qa4+ Nc6
7. e5 $2 {White is being tricky but unfortunately this just doesn't work.} Bxf3
8. exf6 Bd5 $15 {Black is better.}) (6. Bc2 {is also possible.} Nc6 7. O-O e6 {
Transposes.}) 6... Nc6 7. Bc2 e6 8. d3 (8. d4 $6 {is simply premature} cxd4 $1
9. cxd4 Bxf3 10. gxf3 d5 $15 {Black is just better.}) 8... Be7 9. Nbd2 (9. Bf4
O-O 10. Nbd2 d5 {Black is doing good. If White ever pushes e5 we will reach a
better version of Kings Indian Attack for Black.}) 9... O-O 10. Re1 {Planning
Nf1-Ng3. Now, we can plan b5 or d5 or Rc8.} Rc8 $5 {nice move to stay flexible.
} 11. Nf1 h6 {Very important move to preserve our bishop.} 12. Ng3 Bg6 $15 13.
d4 $6 (13. Nh2 {Intending f4 is not working at all.} d5 14. f4 c4 $3 $17 {
Fortunately, the concrete stuff favors us.}) 13... cxd4 14. cxd4 d5 $17 {
Of course! This important move gives us a huge advantage.}) (4. h3 {simply
waiting and stopping Bg4.} g6 $1 {Our plan is to play Bg7 and 0-0.} 5. Bd3 Bg7
6. Bc2 e5 {Intending to capture on d4.} 7. O-O O-O 8. d4 {White needs to play
such a move.} (8. Re1 $6 Nc6 {Black is taking over.}) 8... exd4 9. cxd4 cxd4 $5
{this is the most simple way for an equal-unclear game} 10. Nxd4 Nc6 $11 {
Black has good counterplay and attack against e4 pawn to compensate the weak
d6-pawn.} 11. Nxc6 (11. Nb5 $2 {simply allows} d5 $15 {Black has better
bishops than White.}) 11... bxc6 12. Nc3 d5 (12... Be6 $132 {counterplay!}) 13.
exd5 Nxd5 $132) (4. e5 $2 {This way of playing is very popular common among
amateurs and it is not good at all.} dxe5 5. Nxe5 Nbd7 $15 {The problem is
without really developing his pieces, White is trying to win the game with one
piece and a pawn. This is the totally wrong strategy.} 6. d4 (6. Bb5 {Often in
such positions, White has a feeling that he is pressing but in fact, this is
totally wrong. In fact, Black is better here because White is not well
organized.} a6 7. Bxd7+ Nxd7 {intending to keep the bishop on the board.} 8.
Nxd7 Bxd7 {Black is much better.}) 6... Nxe5 7. dxe5 Qxd1+ 8. Kxd1 Ng4 9. Bb5+
Bd7 10. Bxd7+ Kxd7 {Black will win a pawn soon.}) (4. Qc2 {planning d4.} Qc7 $1
{Whenever you see Qc2 meet it with Qc7. Our idea is to stop d4 once again.} 5.
Be2 g6 $132 {Black has a good version of the dragon.}) 4... g6 $3 {The best
move.} (4... Bd7 $5 $132 {is also possible.}) (4... Nc6 $2 {Again this is a
very common mistake by Black.} 5. d4 $3 {White simply gains a huge advantage
after this move.} cxd4 6. cxd4 Nxe4 7. d5 Qa5+ 8. Nc3 Nxc3 9. bxc3 Ne5 10. Nxe5
Qxc3+ 11. Bd2 Qxe5 12. O-O {White has huge compensation for the sacrificed
pawn. This is almost winning, to be frank.}) (4... Nxe4 $4 5. Qa4+ {oops!}) 5.
O-O (5. Qc2 Qc7 {Again, this is our choice against Qc2.}) 5... Bg7 6. Bb5+ $1 {
The only serious try. The point is to transpose into Bb5 systems where the
fianchetto doesn't make much sense. However, a tempo matters a lot as well!} (
6. Re1 $6 {Another common mistake by club players.} O-O 7. Bf1 {White wants to
play d4 again. But we can simply respond with} Nc6 $1 {...e5 is also possible.}
8. d4 (8. h3 e5 $1 {Black has a perfect Spanish and least an equal game.}) 8...
cxd4 9. cxd4 Bg4 10. d5 Ne5 11. Nbd2 Qa5 $36) (6. d3 $6 {is another passive
try. However, we can simply develop with the following moves} O-O 7. h3 Nc6 8.
Nbd2 e5 $15 9. Re1 h6 10. Bf1 Be6 $15 {Black has a very comfortable position.})
6... Nc6 $1 7. d4 {The best try.} (7. Re1 {would be a bit slow. We can respond
with} O-O 8. d4 (8. h3 {planning to stop Bg4 but it is too slow.} e5 $36 {
stopping d4.} 9. d4 cxd4 10. cxd4 Nxd4 11. Nxd4 exd4 12. Qxd4 {It appears that
White is better because of the weak d6-pawn. But this appearance is completely
deceptive. In fact, Black has a good game because of his active pieces and
counterplay against the e4-pawn.} a6 {chasing the bishop away.} 13. Ba4 b5 14.
Bb3 Re8 {In this open position, Black is better.}) 8... cxd4 9. cxd4 Bg4 $15 {
Unfortunately, White can't stop Bg4 & e5 together. Black is good in this
typical Spanish situation.}) 7... O-O $1 {sidestepping d5 tricks.} 8. d5 (8.
Re1 $6 {falls to} Qb6 $3 $15) (8. e5 Nd7 $132 {We are totally fine after this
simple move.}) (8. dxc5 Nxe4 {important motive to know. We always prefer the
central e4-pawn.}) 8... a6 $3 {You need to memorize this move by heart. The
point is to, follow up with Na5,e6 & b5.} 9. Bd3 (9. Be2 $6 Na5 $1 $15 {
No matter where the Bishop goes we always follow up with Na5 intending b5 & a6.
}) (9. Ba4 $6 Na5 {Following the same strategy.} 10. Bc2 e6 11. dxe6 Bxe6 $132
{planning d5 next.}) 9... Na5 $3 {We will soon strike with b5 or e6.} 10. Bg5 (
10. h3 $6 {is super slow.} e6 $1 11. dxe6 Bxe6 12. Bf4 d5 $15 {solves all the
problem.}) (10. Nbd2 $6 b5 $1 {Black has good counterplay on the queenside.}) (
10. c4 $2 b5 $1 $17 {This is a very good example of the Benoni defense.} 11.
Nc3 (11. cxb5 c4 12. Bc2 axb5 {Black has enough activity to compensate for the
pawn.}) 11... Nxc4 12. Bxc4 bxc4 13. Qc2 e6 $17 {We might even keep our pawn on
c4.}) 10... h6 11. Bh4 b5 12. Nbd2 e5 $1 $132 {With a very good version of the
Spanish!} *

