{A very well played game by Black both in terms of strategy and move orders.}
1. e4 c5 2. Nf3 d6 3. Bc4 {is another line but it is very similar to the
delayed alapin.} Nf6 {By far the most popular and correct move.} (3... Nc6 {
is not recommended. The following moves result into a typical position we wish
to avoid:} 4. O-O Nf6 5. Re1 e6 6. Bb3 Be7 7. c3 O-O 8. d4 cxd4 9. cxd4 {
White is better.}) 4. d3 (4. e5 {is simply premature.} dxe5 5. Nxe5 e6 6. Qe2
Bd6 7. b3 O-O {Black is fine.}) 4... Nc6 5. c3 {planning Bb3-Bc2 and intending
to meet Bg4 with Qb3!} a6 $3 {planning Na5-Nxc4 & Bg4 in case of Bb3.} (5... e6
6. Bb3 Be7 7. O-O O-O 8. Re1) (5... Bg4 {allows} 6. Qb3 {double attack.}) 6.
Bb3 (6. O-O Bg4 7. Qb3 e6 8. Qxb7 Na5 {traps the queen}) (6. a4 {stopping b5;
but it comes with a drawback.} Bg4 7. Qb3 (7. Nbd2 e6 8. O-O Be7) 7... e6 8.
Qxb7 Na5 {traps the queen!}) 6... Bg4 7. Nbd2 e6 8. h3 Bh5 9. Nf1 (9. O-O Be7
10. Re1 O-O 11. Nf1 h6 {our typical way of handling these positions.}) 9... d5
$1 (9... h6 $1 {This move as we know, works perfectly in all these situations
as well!}) 10. exd5 Nxd5 11. Ng3 Bg6 12. O-O Nb6 13. Ne4 Be7 14. Qe2 O-O 15.
Be3 Nd7 16. Rad1 Qc7 17. Bg5 Bxg5 18. Nexg5 h6 19. Ne4 Rad8 20. Rd2 Bh5 21. Ng3
Bxf3 22. Qxf3 Nf6 23. Rfd1 Rd7 24. Ne2 Rfd8 25. Qe3 Ne7 26. g4 Nfd5 27. Qe4 Ng6
28. Qf3 Ndf4 29. d4 Nxe2+ 30. Qxe2 cxd4 31. cxd4 Qf4 32. d5 Ne7 33. Rd4 Qf6 34.
d6 Nc8 35. Qc2 Nxd6 36. Ba4 b5 37. Bb3 Qf3 38. R1d3 Qb7 39. Qd2 Qb6 40. g5 Ne4
41. Rxd7 Rxd7 42. Qe3 Qxe3 43. Rxe3 Nxg5 44. f4 Nh7 45. Rxe6 fxe6 46. Bxe6+ Rf7 0-1

