{[%evp 0,12,14,14,39,52,55,51,76,47,69,67,55,49,48] In this lecture we learn
how to meet the lines of 3.Bb5+ Nd7 Sicilian, where White goes for plans
connected with d2-d4 without c3. The resulting structures are those of the
Open Sicilian and many typical ideas and plans remain similar.} 1. e4 c5 2. Nf3
d6 3. Bb5+ Nd7 4. d4 {This is the main move, after which I recommend an
interesting sideline:} (4. a4 {In this line White anticipates Black's ...a6
move by reinforcing control over the b5 square in order to be able to retreat
with the bishop. Still, the plan is not dangerous against the typical Sicilian
setup:} Ngf6 5. Nc3 e6 6. O-O Be7 7. d4 cxd4 8. Qxd4 O-O {We get good play by
refraining from the ...a6 move for some time, one of the main ideas being ...
Qc7, ...Ne5!}) (4. Ba4 $5 Ngf6 5. O-O {is an interesting modern gambit line.
We will continue unperturbed with} e6 {and get a good version of the Hedgehog
in the main line:} 6. Re1 Be7 7. c4 O-O 8. d4 ({We will also learn to punish
the inadequate} 8. Nc3 $6 {by} Ne5 $1) 8... cxd4 9. Nxd4 Qc7 {planning ...a6, .
.b6 etc.}) 4... cxd4 5. Qxd4 a6 6. Bxd7+ Qxd7 $5 {with original plans including
...e5, ...Qc6, ...Be6 and many times managing without the ...h6 move typical
for the 6...Bxd7 line. Black will get adequate counterplay against White's
play centering around the d5-square.} *

