{[%evp 0,26,58,31,93,31,80,47,79,53,66,66,59,29,45,41,26,33,52,42,29,10,42,42,
49,40,38,-14,26]} 1. e4 c5 2. Nf3 d6 3. Bb5+ Nd7 4. d4 {This is a common and
playable move... with interesting chances for both sides!} (4. O-O {this will
most likely transpose to the lines with d4-cd4 Qxd4} a6 5. Bxd7+ Qxd7 $5) (4.
Ba4 $5 {Very popular for some reason... but really nothing special! A good and
simple set-up is with ... e6-Be7-0-0 and then we are threatening Ne5!} Ngf6 5.
O-O (5. d3 {If White plays slow chess like this, we have time for a kingside
fianchetto, obtaining a great version of the Breyer Ruy Lopez. This is just an
example of this, there is no need for memorization here:} g6 6. O-O Bg7 7. c3
O-O 8. Re1 e5 9. d4 cxd4 10. cxd4 exd4 11. Nxd4 Nc5 $11) 5... e6 {Taking the
pawn on e4 is dangerous, while ...g6 gives White time for c3-d4. I prefer the .
..e6 setup.} 6. Re1 Be7 7. c4 (7. c3 {This is probably the best that White can
do and we transpose to the lines with c3-d4.} a6 8. d4 b5 9. Bc2 Bb7 10. Nbd2
Qc7 $11) (7. d4 cxd4 8. Nxd4 O-O $11 {is just a good version of the Open
Sicilian for Black.}) 7... O-O 8. Nc3 $6 {A generic move, not taking into
account the ...Ne5 resource. But played most often here!} (8. d4 $5 cxd4 9.
Nxd4 (9. Qxd4 $6 Qc7 $15 {Black is already slightly better. White has a bad
version of the Hedghehog with a misplaced light-squared bishop.} 10. Nc3 Ne5 $3
$15 {This is a much better option than the automatic ...a6 played in
Svidler-Dominguez Perez.} 11. Nxe5 dxe5 12. Qd3 Bd7 13. Bxd7 Rfd8 $3 14. Qe2
Rxd7 {In the resulting game we have strong outposts for our pieces while White
is passive, e.g.} 15. Be3 Bb4 $3 $17 {Exploiting the weaknesses.}) 9... Qc7 10.
Bb3 (10. Nc3 $6 Qxc4 $15 11. Ndb5 Ne5) (10. Na3 a6 11. Bd2 (11. f3 d5) 11...
Nc5 12. Bc2 b6 13. Rc1 Bb7 $132) 10... a6 11. Nc3 b6 12. h3 Bb7 13. Qe2 Rfe8
$132 {with a good version of the Hedgehog for Black!}) 8... Ne5 $1 {It seems
that black is already slightly better!} 9. Nxe5 (9. d3 Bd7 $1 ({Or} 9... Nfd7
$1 {See the game Vokhidov-Tabatabaei.}) 10. Bxd7 Nfxd7 $36 11. Rb1 Bf6) 9...
dxe5 10. d3 Bd7 11. Bxd7 (11. Be3 Bxa4 12. Nxa4 b6 13. Qe2 Nd7 14. Rad1 Nb8 15.
Qg4 Nc6 $17) 11... Nxd7 12. Be3 Nb8 $15 {Black transfers the knight to the
best square with an advantage.} 13. Qd2 Nc6 14. Rad1 b6 15. f4 exf4 16. Bxf4
Qd4+ $17 {0-1 Sakir, R-Gokerkan,C/Konya}) (4. a4 $5 {Another playable
alternative that should not cause any problems.} Ngf6 $1 5. Nc3 {and now we
have a few good ways for an unclear game with chances for both sides ...} (5.
d3 $6 {Very passive... here is a nice example of what plan to follow in such a
position...} a6 6. Bc4 e6 {Threatening the immediate ...d5.} 7. Nc3 b6 $1 $36
8. O-O Bb7 9. Re1 Be7 10. Bf4 O-O 11. h3 Qc8 $1 {Intending ...Bc6 and ...Qb7
with a full harmony.} 12. Nd2 Bc6 13. Qe2 Qb7 14. Bb3 b5 $36 {White starts
paying the price for "getting out of book" with 5.d3?!}) 5... e6 $5 {I suggest
to play without ...a6 once again.} (5... g6 $5 {is also good}) 6. d4 (6. a5 Be7
7. O-O (7. a6 $2 {This move appears to be good but in fact its not a threat at
all!} O-O 8. O-O (8. axb7 Bxb7 9. d3 a6 10. Ba4 Nb6 $15 (10... c4 $5 $15 {
is also very good.} 11. O-O Nc5 12. Be3 Qc7 $15) 11. Bb3 a5 $15 {With very
unpleasant ideas of ...a4, . ..c4 and ...d5.}) 8... bxa6 $3 9. Bxa6 Bxa6 10.
Rxa6 c4 $3 $15 {A line to remember! We are preparing ...Nc5.} 11. Qe2 (11. d4
cxd3 12. cxd3 Nc5 13. Ra2 a5 {Stopping b2-b4.} 14. Re1 d5 $15 15. e5 Nfd7 16.
d4 Na6 {The knight comes to b4. Black is practically better, as he has some
queenside play while there is absolutely no attack on the kingside by White.})
11... Nc5 12. Ra1 d5 13. exd5 exd5 {The position may be close to equality, but
we in fact have a slight positional edge in all lines:} 14. d4 cxd3 (14... Nce4
$15) 15. cxd3 Re8 $15) 7... O-O 8. d4 cxd4 9. Qxd4 $1 (9. Nxd4 a6 10. Be2 Nc5
11. Bf3 Rb8 12. Be3 Qc7 $132 {with a great Open Sicilian.}) 9... a6 10. Be2 Qc7
{The universal idea now is ...Ne5.} 11. h3 Ne5 $1 12. Nxe5 dxe5 13. Qc4 Qxc4
14. Bxc4 Bd7 $132 {Black can be very comfortable in this endgame, with play on
the c-file and against the a5-pawn.}) (6. O-O Be7 7. d4 cxd4 8. Qxd4 {
transposes to 6.d4}) 6... cxd4 7. Qxd4 Be7 8. O-O O-O {With typical play...} 9.
Rd1 (9. Be3 $6 {This move runs into .. .Ng4.} a6 10. Be2 Ng4 11. Bc1 b6 12. h3
Ngf6 $36) 9... Qc7 {We are setting up the ...Ne5 idea, but also ..b6} 10. h3 (
10. Be3 Ne5 $132) 10... b6 $5 (10... Ne5 $132) (10... Rd8 $1 $132) 11. Bxd7 (
11. Be3 Bb7 $36) 11... Qxd7 12. Be3 Qc7 $132) 4... cxd4 5. Qxd4 a6 6. Bxd7+
Qxd7 $1 {An interesting line similar to 6...Bxd7, but a bit more rare and a
bit more interesting!} 7. Nc3 (7. O-O $1 e5 $1 (7... Qc6 $1) 8. Qd3 Qc6 $1 9.
c4 {Whenever we see c4, we should strike with ...b5 soon.} (9. Re1 {This is
like the main line with the rook on e1 instead of d1.} Be6 10. Nc3 Nf6 $5 (
10... h6 $132) 11. Bg5 Nd7 $1 12. a4 h6 $36) 9... Be6 10. b3 b5 11. cxb5 Qxb5
$1 $132 {Taking with the pawn is also correct, but this gains a tempo by
threatening the white queen. The queen exchange is of course completely fine
for us.}) (7. Bg5 $2 {Hitting into... nowhere!} e5 8. Qd3 h6 9. Be3 (9. Bh4 g5
10. Bg3 f5 $15 {Even more desirable than 10...Nf6. We are not worried about
the weakening of the light squares, as we are the side with the light-squared
bishop.}) 9... Nf6 $15) (7. c4 e5 8. Qd3 f5 $1 9. Nc3 Nf6 10. Bg5 $2 (10. Nd2
b5 $1 11. O-O Be7 $132 (11... Bb7 $132)) (10. O-O fxe4 11. Nxe4 Nxe4 12. Qxe4
Qf5 $132) (10. exf5 $6 Qxf5 11. Qe2 (11. Qxf5 $2 Bxf5 12. b3 Rc8 $17) 11... Qg6
$36 12. O-O Bg4 13. Re1 Rc8 14. b3 Be7 15. Ba3 O-O $36) 10... fxe4 $1 11. Nxe4
Nxe4 12. Qxe4 Qg4 $15 13. Qxg4 Bxg4 14. Nd2 b5 $15 15. b3 Rc8 16. O-O h6 17.
Be3 Be7 18. f4 bxc4 19. Nxc4 Be2 20. Nb6 Rc3 21. Nd5 Rd3 22. Rfe1 Rxd5 23. Rxe2
{1/2-1/2 Munoz Pantoja,M-Sankalp,G/Barbera del Valles ESP 2021}) 7... e5 $1 8.
Qd3 (8. Qb6 $5 Qc6 9. Nd5 Qxb6 10. Nxb6 Rb8 11. Be3 (11. Nxc8 $2 Rxc8 12. c3
Nf6 {White's knight is way too far from d5!} 13. Nd2 d5 $17 {With a big endgame
advantage.} 14. exd5 Nxd5 15. O-O f6 $17 {Intending ...Kf7. White's queenside
pawn majority is irrelevant.}) 11... Nf6 $5 {We have an unclear game. Black
lost in the following game, but it was only due to a late game blunder:} 12.
Nd2 Be6 13. c4 Be7 14. f3 Nd7 15. Nd5 Bd8 $6 ({I recommend improving Black's
play with} 15... Rc8 $1 $132 {with ideas of ...f5.}) 16. Ke2 g6 17. a4 f5 18.
a5 h5 19. b4 Nf6 20. Rhb1 fxe4 21. Nxf6+ Bxf6 22. fxe4 Rc8 23. Kd3 Rh7 24. b5
Bd8 25. bxa6 bxa6 26. Rb6 Bxb6 27. axb6 Ra8 28. Nb3 Rf7 29. Na5 Bc8 30. Rd1 Rd7
31. Rf1 Rf7 32. Rd1 Rd7 33. h4 Rb8 34. Nc6 Ra8 35. Na5 Rb8 36. Kc3 Bb7 37. Nxb7
Rbxb7 38. Kb4 Rb8 39. Ka5 Rc8 40. c5 dxc5 41. Rxd7 Kxd7 42. b7 Re8 43. Kb6 c4
44. Bd2 {1-0 Svane, R-Cheparinov,I/Krasnaya Polyana RUS 2021}) 8... Qc6 $1 9.
O-O (9. Be3 $2 {This square is for a knight!} Be6 {White cannot castle short
because of ...Bc4.} 10. O-O-O (10. Nd2 Nf6 11. O-O $6 (11. Bg5 Nd7 $15 {
The typical response to Bg5 in this line. Black is doing well. He can kick the
bishop out by ...h6.}) 11... d5 $17 {The typical opening of the game for the
bishop pair.}) 10... Rc8 $15 {Sometimes ...f5 ideas come up, e.g. 11.Nd5 f5!?
In general Black is happy, as White is not well prepared to attack on the
kingside having a knight on f3.}) (9. Nd5 Nf6 $1 {Black is completely fine
based on the correct evaluation of the unbalancing 10.Nxf6+ move:} (9... Ne7 $5
$132 {is an alternative.}) 10. Nxf6+ $6 gxf6 $15 {White will not succeed in
trying to exploit the f5-square:} 11. Nh4 $2 Be6 $17 {With ...Bc4 and ..d5
ideas. White's flank play will not be successful against Black's central
action.}) (9. a4 $2 Be6 10. Be3 Nf6 $15) 9... Be6 10. Rd1 $1 (10. b3 $2 {
A very ineffective development scheme.} Rc8 11. Bb2 h6 $6 {There's no need to
waste a tempo on this, as there is no Bg5. Anyway, Black won a nice game:} (
11... Be7 $1 $15) 12. Rfd1 Nf6 13. Rac1 Be7 $132 14. Nd2 O-O 15. Nf1 Nd7 16.
Nd5 Bg5 17. Nde3 Be7 18. Nd5 Bxd5 19. exd5 Qc7 20. c4 f5 21. b4 e4 22. Qb3 Bf6
23. Bxf6 Rxf6 24. c5 Ne5 25. cxd6 Qxc1 26. Rxc1 Rxc1 27. Qb2 Nf3+ {0-1 Verheul,
J-Sonneveld,D/ Almelo NED 2021}) (10. Nd5 $4 f5 $3 $17 {A huge problem for
White!} 11. c4 fxe4 12. Qxe4 Nf6 $17 {White's centre collapses.}) (10. Nd2 {
Yes, White can manuver the knight to e3, but Black will get plenty of play in
the meantime:} Nf6 11. Re1 b5 $15) 10... Nf6 $5 {This move works well with the
queen on c6 and the bishop on e6, as we are ready to meet Bg5 by ...Nd7.} (
10... Rc8 11. Nd2 (11. a4 Nf6 12. Bg5 Nd7 $132 {See Melia-Can}) 11... g6 $3 $15
{An amazing move by the computer! The idea is to create a King's Indian style
pawn avalanche on the kingside.} (11... Nf6 $5 {This is also good with typical
play!} 12. Nf1 Qc4 13. Ne3 Qxd3 14. cxd3 Be7 $132) 12. Nf1 f5 13. Ne3 f4 14.
Ned5 Kf7 $3 {More high-level computer play.} 15. Bd2 g5 16. f3 Nf6 $15 {
Black can even take with the king on f6 and still he will be the one attacking
after preparing ...g4!} (16... Be7 $15) (16... h5 $15)) 11. Bg5 Nd7 $3 $132 {
The point, as mentioned above.} 12. Nd5 Nc5 13. Qc4 (13. Qe2 $6 f5 $15 {
White's centre falls!}) 13... Rc8 $132 {Black has quite a few strong ideas now:
...Nd7, ...Bxd5 and ...f5. He has excellent prospects for the future.} *

