{[%evp 0,68,24,16,52,52,73,31,54,67,42,16,33,25,23,33,6,7,34,-6,16,8,2,-11,-7,
-10,-13,-41,-27,-26,-7,-30,-9,-23,-5,-27,-22,-84,-82,-73,-74,-116,-89,-75,-55,
-60,-62,-64,-60,-78,-92,-91,-97,-128,-97,-98,-104,-118,-124,-168,-186,-169,
-171,-190,-189,-191,-190,-215,-224,-224,-262]} 1. e4 c5 2. Nf3 d6 3. Bb5+ Nd7
4. O-O a6 5. Bxd7+ Bxd7 {Black plays ...Bxd7, not ...Qxd7, but the ideas are
similar.} 6. d4 cxd4 7. Qxd4 e5 8. Qd3 Qc7 9. Nc3 Be6 10. b3 $2 {A pretty bad
development scheme, which is mentioned in the theory part as well. The bishop
will shoot into the solid e5-pawn and in addition be blocked by the knight. It
also softens the c3-point, which should rather be kept well-fortified.} ({
A normal choice would be} 10. Nd2 Nf6) (10. Nd5 Bxd5 11. Qxd5 {White doesn't
achieve anything here, because her remaining knight is too far from the
d5-square.} Nf6 12. Qd3 Rc8 13. c3 (13. Bg5 $6 Qxc2 14. Qa3 $1 {offers some
compensation, but is not so attractive, even to the engine, which suggests it.}
) 13... h6 $11 {White will never get the desired Bg5-xf6 and Nd5.}) 10... Rc8
11. Bb2 Be7 12. Rfd1 Nf6 13. Nd2 b5 14. a3 O-O 15. Nf1 Qb7 16. Ne3 Rc5 $1 {
An important idea. The rook ensures that White has to take with the pawn at
the end of any Nd5 variation.} 17. Rac1 Rfc8 18. Ncd5 $6 {White finally sees
no other useful move, but this only worsens her situation.} Nxd5 19. exd5 Bd7
20. c3 Bg5 $1 21. Rc2 Bxe3 $1 {A high-level decision. Black parts with the
bishop pair to obtain a strategically won opposite-coloured bishops position.
Black won easily.} 22. fxe3 a5 23. e4 a4 24. bxa4 bxa4 25. c4 Qb3 26. Kf2 Rxc4
27. Rxc4 Rxc4 28. Qxb3 axb3 29. Ke3 f5 30. exf5 Bxf5 31. Rd2 Kf7 32. Kf3 Ke7
33. h3 h5 34. Re2 Bd3 35. Rd2 Be4+ 36. Ke3 h4 37. Ba1 Rc2 0-1

