{[%evp 0,116,19,38,40,41,66,65,75,46,74,69,59,53,51,9,61,81,74,-4,3,-23,-21,
-14,-12,-20,-7,-17,-27,-20,-13,-13,-10,0,0,0,15,15,11,-28,-12,-12,0,8,35,8,15,
11,1,-8,-8,-15,-30,-15,-25,-85,-18,-13,-15,-18,-17,-5,0,0,-15,-10,-7,-44,-48,
-23,-21,-63,-69,-110,-145,-141,-143,-143,-142,-169,-112,-112,-116,-104,-115,
-103,-55,-55,-91,-94,-54,-73,-72,-72,-62,-62,-62,-95,-104,-104,-106,-123,-135,
-120,-109,-137,-139,-139,-148,-247,-247,-247,-275,-452,-275,-247,-247,-507,
-527]} 1. e4 c5 2. Nf3 d6 3. Bb5+ Nd7 4. d4 cxd4 5. Qxd4 a6 6. Bxd7+ Bxd7 {
My recommended line is 6...Qxd7, but a lot of general features of the game
remain the same for both moves, so we can learn from games from this line as
well.} 7. O-O Rc8 8. Nc3 e5 9. Qd3 h6 10. Nd2 Qc7 11. Rd1 Nf6 12. Nf1 Be7 13.
Ne3 Be6 14. Bd2 (14. Ncd5 $2 {leads to a bad overextension:} Nxd5 15. exd5 Bd7
$17 16. c4 $6 O-O $19 {How is White supposed to deal with ...f5?}) 14... O-O
15. Rac1 b5 16. Ncd5 Nxd5 17. Nxd5 Bxd5 18. Qxd5 Qc4 19. Be3 Qxd5 20. Rxd5 Rc6
$15 {Black is slightly better in this endgame. Compared to Black, White has no
target. Black's general idea in this type of position is always to put the
king on e6. He needs to push the f-pawn first to allow that.} 21. c3 h5 {
Black prepares ...g6 and ...f5 by stepping out of Bxh6.} ({Black doesn't want
too many simplifications:} 21... f5 22. exf5 Rxf5 23. f4 $11) ({Naither does
he want to play the anti-positional} 21... f6 {, although it is objectively
fine.}) 22. Kf1 (22. f4 $5 {was an interesting try to keep the balance.}) 22...
g6 23. Ke2 f5 24. f3 $6 {Too passive.} ({White should have fought Black's idea
by} 24. exf5 gxf5 25. f4 $11 {, keeping the equal chances.}) 24... Kf7 25. Kd3
Ke6 26. Ra1 Rb8 27. b4 Rbc8 28. Bd2 Rc4 29. a4 Rxe4 $1 {An amazing tactical
idea.} 30. Rxd6+ Bxd6 31. fxe4 Rc4 32. axb5 axb5 33. exf5+ $2 {White falters,
but the correct line was hard to find.} (33. Ra5 $1 Rxe4 34. h3 $3 $11 {
, stopping ...Rg4, kept the balance. This is of course a computer resource.})
33... gxf5 34. Ra6 Rc8 $2 {Missing a better chance.} (34... Rg4 $1 35. g3 h4 $1
$19 {shatters White's structure and wins!}) 35. Be3 Kd5 36. g3 $4 {This allows
Black to break through.} (36. Rb6 Rb8 37. Rxb5+ Rxb5 38. c4+ Kc6 39. cxb5+ Kxb5
40. h3 {and g3-g4! should have still held comfortably.}) 36... e4+ 37. Kd2 Be5
38. Bc5 Kc4 39. Rh6 Rd8+ 40. Ke2 Bxc3 41. Rxh5 Rd2+ 42. Ke3 Rd5 43. Ke2 Rd2+
44. Ke3 Rd3+ $4 {Very uneccessary.} ({Black should have went back to the
previous line and captured on b4:} 44... Rd5 45. Ke2 Bxb4 46. Bxb4 Kxb4 47. g4
Kc5 48. gxf5 b4 $19 {with a completely won rook endgame.}) 45. Ke2 Rf3 46. Rg5
Bxb4 47. Bxb4 Kxb4 48. g4 $4 {And now finally White loses.} (48. h4 $1 $11 {
The h-pawn is quick and allows White to draw.}) 48... Kc5 49. gxf5 b4 50. f6+
Kc4 51. Re5 Rxf6 52. Rxe4+ Kc3 53. Re8 Rh6 54. Rc8+ Kb2 55. Kd3 Rh3+ 56. Kd4
Rxh2 57. Rb8 b3 58. Kc4 Kc2 0-1

