{[%evp 0,90,25,11,55,39,67,64,59,59,42,40,40,40,22,3,35,6,7,26,24,28,42,54,43,
34,36,27,28,0,5,9,21,12,12,9,9,-21,-10,-12,0,-13,-14,-13,0,-16,-22,-35,-33,-42,
-37,-38,-26,-25,-30,-31,0,0,-5,0,0,-10,-6,-5,0,-25,-19,-131,-80,-102,-120,-100,
-102,-118,-111,-129,-124,-146,-153,-192,-190,-202,-202,-257,-210,-264,-238,
-230,-192,-191,-93,-252,-466] Here is a nice effort of myself... an
instructive example of the endgames with the king on e6 ! It doesnt matter if
the move 6...Bxd7 was chosen instead of ...Qxd7, we can learn because the type
of position is the same.} 1. e4 c5 2. Nf3 d6 3. Bb5+ Nd7 4. d4 cxd4 5. Qxd4 a6
6. Bxd7+ Bxd7 7. c4 b5 {Remember, whenever White plays c4, you keep the
typical ideas and add ...b5 to them.} 8. Nc3 e5 9. Qd3 bxc4 10. Qxc4 Qc8 ({
White has a concrete idea of winning a pawn after} 10... h6 {:} 11. Nd5 $1 Rc8
12. Qxa6 Nf6 13. Nxf6+ Qxf6 14. O-O Be7 $44 {Still, Black has some
compensation.}) 11. Qd3 h6 {We have reached the typical position without the c
and b pawns.} 12. O-O Nf6 13. Nd2 Be6 14. Rd1 (14. f4 $2 {is wrong. This is
not a Najdorf!} exf4 15. Rxf4 Be7 $15 {with very good play for Black. White
has only weakened a number of squares in his camp.}) 14... Be7 15. Nf1 Qb7 $1
16. Ne3 Rc8 $1 {I keep my king on e8 for a reason!} (16... O-O 17. Ned5 Bxd5
18. Nxd5 Nxd5 19. Qxd5 Qxd5 20. Rxd5 Rfc8 21. Bd2 {X Kg8}) 17. Ned5 Nxd5 18.
Nxd5 (18. exd5 $2 Bg4 $3 19. Re1 Bh5 $17 {The bishop obtains an excellent
diagonal.}) 18... Bxd5 19. Qxd5 Qxd5 20. Rxd5 Kd7 $1 {The point of keeping the
king in the centre.} 21. Bd2 Ke6 22. Ra5 Rc6 23. Kf1 Rb8 ({It was better to
prevent Rc1.} 23... Rhc8 $5 24. Bc3 Bd8 $15 25. Ra4 f5) 24. Rc1 $1 Rxc1+ 25.
Bxc1 Rb6 26. Ke2 Rc6 27. Be3 Rc2+ 28. Kd3 Rxb2 29. Rxa6 {White is close to a
draw, but I managed to create some winning chances:} f5 $5 ({The bishops trade
doesn't achieve much:} 29... Bg5 30. a4 Bxe3 31. Kxe3 Rb3+ 32. Ke2 g6 33. a5
$11) 30. a4 fxe4+ 31. Kxe4 h5 $5 32. a5 $6 Ra2 $1 $15 {Now Black gets checks on
a4! A draw is no longer an obvious matter.} 33. f4 $2 {An immediate huge
mistake.} Ra4+ 34. Kd3 ({Or} 34. Kf3 e4+ 35. Kf2 Ra2+ 36. Kf1 Kd5 37. Ra8 Kc4
$19 {Black pieces and pawns work perfectly together and overwhelm White.})
34... exf4 $6 (34... e4+ $1 {was much more accurate, creating two connected
passed pawns:} 35. Kc2 Bf6 $1 $19 {White will surely not be able to hold the
position.}) 35. Bb6 Kd5 $2 (35... Ra2 $1 {was better, with a sudden mating
idea, hard to spot over the board:} 36. Ra8 d5 $1 37. a6 $2 Bb4 $1 $19) 36. Ra7
$6 (36. Ra8 $5 {with the immediate a-pawn counterplay drew:} Ra3+ 37. Ke2 Bf6
38. a6 Bd4 39. Bxd4 Kxd4 40. a7 h4 41. Rd8 Rxa7 42. Rxd6+ Ke4 43. Re6+ Kf5 44.
Rc6 Ra2+ 45. Kf1 h3 46. gxh3 Rxh2 47. Rc3 $11) 36... Bf6 $17 37. Rc7 $2 ({
Even with the loss of a tempo, White should stick with} 37. Ra8 $15) 37... Ra3+
38. Kc2 g5 $1 $19 39. h4 gxh4 40. Rh7 Ke4 41. Rxh5 Ra2+ 42. Kd1 (42. Kb3 Rxg2
43. a6 Rb2+ 44. Ka4 Rxb6 45. a7 Ra6+ 46. Ra5 Rxa7 47. Rxa7 f3 $19) 42... d5 $3
{In such positions the key is... ALWAYS PLAY AGAINST THE KING!... ALWAYS PLAY
FOR CHECKMATE!} 43. Rh6 Bc3 44. Rxh4 d4 $1 45. Bc7 (45. g3 Kd3) 45... Bd2 $1 {
White resigned due to unavoidable checkmate.} 0-1

