-375,-372,-445,-446,-500,-529,-501,-500,-669,-673,-678,-668,-747,-761,-777,
-792,-902,-919,-997,-1034,-1217,-1100,-1173,-1194,-1320,-1242,-1331,-1252,
-1410,-1300,-1940,-1775] White overextends and his position falls apart
completely.} 1. e4 c5 2. Nf3 d6 3. Bb5+ Nd7 4. a4 Ngf6 5. Nc3 e6 6. O-O Be7 7.
d4 cxd4 8. Qxd4 O-O 9. Rd1 a6 10. Be2 Qc7 11. Nd2 Ne5 12. f4 $2 {A move
showing an extreme over-optimism or simply a lack of understanding. White
can't afford to extend like that with his pieces still standing in each other's
way.} Nc6 13. Qf2 Nb4 $1 {A swift punishment comes.} 14. Nc4 d5 $2 ({The
simple and consistent} 14... Nxc2 $1 $19 {was the right choice.}) 15. Nb6 $2 {
White misses his chance to stay in the game.} (15. exd5 $1 Nbxd5 16. Nxd5 Nxd5
17. Kh1 $15 {was unpleasant for White, but still playable.}) 15... Rb8 {
Two many targets in White's camp are under attack and there are no saving
possibilities.} 16. e5 Nxc2 $1 {Perhaps White missed this resource. 17.exf6 is
met by 17...Bc5.} 17. Kh1 Nxa1 $6 (17... Ne4 $1 $19 {was the more accurate
conversion.}) 18. exf6 Bxf6 19. Bd3 $2 (19. f5 $1 $17 {was the last chance to
avert disaster. White gets some active ideas.}) 19... Nb3 20. a5 Nxa5 21. Nca4
Nb3 22. Be3 d4 23. Bd2 Bd7 24. Bb4 Bxa4 25. Nxa4 Rfc8 26. Qf3 b5 27. f5 bxa4
28. fxe6 Rxb4 29. Qf5 fxe6 30. Qxh7+ Kf7 31. Qh5+ Ke7 32. Re1 Rb6 33. g4 Qc5
34. Qg6 Qg5 35. Qe4 Rc1 0-1

