{[%evp 0,36,17,19,33,45,71,41,48,42,52,23,25,-4,1,-12,-9,-7,-7,-22,-22,-9,-9,
-20,-20,-20,-25,-25,-15,-15,-15,-9,8,8,-2,0,10,10,13]} 1. e4 c5 2. Nf3 d6 3.
Bb5+ Nd7 4. O-O (4. c3 $5 {This is a playable system... similar to the main
line... but after the fast 4...Ngf6!, white is forced to protect his e4 pawn
with Qe2, which is a less desirable move than Re1!} Ngf6 $1 5. Qe2 (5. Bd3 a6
$1 {transpositions}) 5... a6 6. Ba4 (6. Bd3 e6 7. O-O Be7 8. a4 b6) 6... b5 7.
Bc2 Bb7 8. d4 e6 9. O-O Be7 {and this Qe2 move is a bit premature... Black has
good counterplay:} 10. Nbd2 Qc7 $3 {Black has a very concrete idea in mind.}
11. Bd3 (11. Re1 {allows a pretty favourable change of structure:} cxd4 12.
Nxd4 O-O $132) (11. e5 dxe5 12. dxe5 Nd5 $132 {Black has the ideas of ...Nf4
and even ...g5 and White can't play Ne4 because the pawn on e5 hangs.}) 11...
Nh5 $3 $132 {And this nice idea highlights the problems of a fast Qe2 move.}
12. g3 {This move is more or less forced but it creates long term weaknesses!}
(12. Qe3 {is awkward. Black has great aggressive ideas available against it.}
O-O 13. Re1 e5 $1 14. a4 (14. g3 $6 {is a weakening:} Nhf6 $15 15. d5 c4 16.
Bc2 Ng4 17. Qe2 f5 18. exf5 Bxd5 $15) (14. d5 $2 {This move may appear logical,
but it is an instructive mistake.} c4 15. Bc2 Nf4 16. g3 Nd3 17. Bxd3 cxd3 18.
Qxd3 f5 $17 19. exf5 Nc5 20. Qe2 Bxd5) 14... Nf4 15. Bf1 c4 $132 {Black intends
...f5, with perfect play.}) 12... Nhf6 13. b3 O-O 14. Re1 Rfe8 $132 {We have a
very good game. Our hope is that the g2-g3 move will ultimately backfire,
possibly with the game opening and the weakness of the long diagonal becoming
more pronounced and problematic for White.} (14... Rac8 $132 {is a viable
alternative.})) 4... a6 $1 {The most accurate. 4...Ngf6 5.Re1 allows White to
hide the bishop on f1.} 5. Bd3 Ngf6 6. c3 (6. Re1 {AFTER 6.Re1, WHITE IS NOT
SO FAST WITH c3-d4 SO BLACK IS IN TIME TO PLAY ...g6!-Bg7! ...g6 does not seem
to be so good after the fast 6.c3} g6 $1 7. c3 (7. Bf1 $5 Bg7 8. d4 (8. c3 b5
$1 $132) 8... cxd4 9. Qxd4 O-O) 7... Bg7 8. Bc2 O-O $1 {SOS!! ONE OF THE
SIMPLEST AND BEST LINES FOR BLACK!... AFTER 6.Re1-g6! we have enough time!!...
but not after 6.c3} 9. d4 (9. d3 $2 {Too passive.} b5 10. Nbd2 Bb7 11. Nf1 e5
12. Ng3 (12. Bg5 h6) 12... Re8 $15 {Black is already better, with a vastly
improved version of the Breyer.} 13. d4 (13. h3 d5 $15) 13... cxd4 14. cxd4
exd4 15. Nxd4 d5 $3 $19 {0-1 Tekeyev,Z-Nepomniachtchi,I/Sochi RUS 2018/[,})
9... e5 $1 10. dxe5 (10. d5 $6 b5 $1 11. a4 Nb6 $5 12. h3 (12. a5 Nbd7 $15 {
White has no play on the queenside now and Black can start slowly but surely
the KID-type play on the kingside.}) 12... Bd7 $15 13. a5 Nc8 $3 {Black has
potential for KID-type play. The game Berdayes-Sardana showcases this idea.}) (
10. a4 $1 {For some reason this move appears to be the best!} Rb8 $3 {It turns
out we need not fear 12.a5} (10... exd4 $1 {This is the most direct way!} 11.
cxd4 cxd4 12. Nxd4 Ng4 $1 $132 {The most interesting choice.} (12... Re8 13.
Nc3 d5 $5 {This was played by Gajewski, a good analytician. Black equalizes
easily.} 14. exd5 (14. Nxd5 $4 Nxd5 15. exd5 Rxe1+ 16. Qxe1 Bxd4) 14... Rxe1+
15. Qxe1 Nb6 16. Bg5 Nbxd5 17. Bb3 Nxc3 18. bxc3 Bd7 $132) 13. Qxg4 Bxd4 {
The bishop on d4 is a nuisance for White.} 14. Nc3 Nf6 15. Qd1 (15. Qh4 $4 Ng4
$19) 15... Qb6 16. Qd2 Bd7 17. a5 Qc5 {It can be argued Black has the worse
structure, but on the other hand he is active and some of White's pieces remain
stuck.} 18. Rd1 Be5 $132) 11. dxe5 $1 (11. a5 $2 b5 $3 {A wonderful idea
pointed out by the computer! After axb6 the black queen will arrive on b6 at
the right moment:} 12. axb6 cxd4 $3 13. cxd4 exd4 14. Nxd4 Qxb6 (14... Ng4 $5
$36) 15. Nc3 Ne5 $36 (15... Re8 $36)) (11. d5 b5 12. axb5 axb5 13. Nbd2 c4 $15
{The game concentrates around the queenside, and we have an easier game there,
e.g.} 14. b4 cxb3 15. Nxb3 Nb6 16. Bd3 Bd7 17. Ba3 Qc7 18. Bb4 Bh6 19. Qe2 Na4
$36) 11... Nxe5 12. Nxe5 dxe5 13. Qxd8 Rxd8 14. Be3 b6 (14... Bf8 $1 15. Bg5 (
15. f3 Be6 16. a5 c4 17. Nd2 Nd7 $15 18. Red1 Nc5 $1 (18... Bc5)) 15... Kg7)
15. a5 (15. f3 c4 16. Nd2 Be6 $15 17. Kf1 Nd7) 15... Be6 16. axb6 Rxb6 17. b4
Bf8 18. f3 (18. Nd2 $4 Ng4 $19) 18... Rc6 (18... Nd7) 19. bxc5 Bxc5 20. Bxc5
Rxc5 21. Rxa6 Rb5 $11) (10. h3 b5 $1 {Typical expansion.} ({Immediate
exchanges are a good alternative:} 10... exd4 $1 11. cxd4 cxd4 12. Nxd4 Re8 13.
Nc3 b5 $132 {with great active play, e.g.} 14. Nc6 Qc7 15. Nb4 Bb7 $132) 11. a4
Rb8 $132 {We hope for a good version of the Breyer, where we don't put the
bishop on b7, in order to reach the d7-square in one go after the centre
closes:} 12. d5 c4 ({Do not commit the strategical mistake of} 12... Qc7 $2 13.
b3 $1 {and ...c4 is met by b3-b4, so we will not get the knight to c5 anymore.}
) 13. Nbd2 Nc5 14. Nf1 Bd7 (14... bxa4 $5 {is also good and leads to a
different type of game. 14...Bd7 is more clear.}) 15. axb5 axb5 (15... Bxb5 {
is interesting, but objectively a bit worse than the pawn capture.}) 16. Ng3
Ra8 $132 {We have a great version of the classical Breyer, with absolutely no
problems.}) (10. Nbd2 $2 {With a misplaced knight on d2, it is the best moment
for the double capture! It leads to an advantage for Black!!} cxd4 $1 11. cxd4
exd4 $1 12. Nxd4 Re8 $17 13. h3 b5 $1 $17 14. a4 bxa4 15. Rxa4 Bb7 $15 {
White is very uncomfortable with his passive pieces and weak control of the
centre.}) 10... Nxe5 $1 {Of course we free our pieces up rather than passively
capturing with the pawn.} 11. Nxe5 dxe5 12. Be3 (12. Qxd8 Rxd8 13. Be3 c4 $1 (
13... Bf8 {Also a good move with a slightly better game.} 14. f3 b5 15. Nd2 Be6
$15) 14. Nd2 Be6 15. Nf3 (15. f3 b5 $15) (15. Rad1 Ng4 $1 16. Bg5 Bf6 (16... f6
$5 17. Bh4 Kf7 18. f3 Nh6) 17. Bxf6 Nxf6 $15 {Black is better in this endgame
thanks to the restricting pawn on c4 and the passive bishop on c2. Here is a
sample line:} 18. Nf3 Nd7 (18... Rxd1 $5 19. Rxd1 Bg4) 19. Ng5 Nc5 20. Nxe6
Nxe6 21. Rxd8+ Rxd8 22. Rd1 Rxd1+ 23. Bxd1 Nc5 $15 {Such an edngame may be
objectively drawn, but we can play for a win with Black with absolutely no
risk. Don't give the opponent a draw!}) 15... Ng4 16. Bd2 f6 17. h3 Nh6 18. Be3
Nf7 19. Rad1 b5 $15 (19... Bh6 20. Bxh6 Nxh6 21. Nd4 Kf7 22. Nxe6 Kxe6 23. g3
Nf7 24. Kf1 Rxd1 25. Rxd1 Nd6 (25... Rd8))) (12. c4 $6 {This is an attempt to
gain control over the d5-square with Nc3 next, but is too fast with his
counterplay:} b5 13. Qxd8 (13. Nc3 {We happily take the pawn in this scenario:}
bxc4 $15) 13... Rxd8 14. b3 Be6 $15 {White has no time for Nc3-d5.}) (12. a4 $6
{White wants to fix our structure, but we have our own idea of fixing White's
pawns!} Be6 13. Qe2 c4 $1 $15 {We have acquired ideas of ...Nd7-c5 in addition
to the ...Nh5-f4 options. Black is a bit more comfortable.}) 12... Qc7 13. a4 (
13. f3 $2 b5 $15) 13... Be6 14. a5 Ng4 $1 (14... b5 $5 $132 15. axb6 Qxb6 16.
b4 Rfd8 17. Qf3 Nd7 $132 18. Ba4 Bf8) 15. Bd2 (15. Bg5 h6 16. Bh4 Bf6 $3 $15
17. Bg3 $2 (17. Bxf6 Nxf6 $17) 17... h5 18. h3 h4 $19) 15... Bh6 $3 $15 {
In such positions it is always good to trade the dark-squared bishops!!}) (6.
c4 $6 {Possible, but not very good.} Ne5 $1 {We typically choose ...Ne5 if the
white pawn appears on c4, not if it is on c3. This is because the d4-square
gets seriously weakened.} 7. Nxe5 dxe5 8. Bc2 e6 9. d3 Bd6 $15 {In the long
term Black wants to transfer the knight towards d4 via d7-b8-c6.}) 6... e6 $1 {
We are waiting for Bc2 and then we play ...b5!} 7. Re1 (7. Bc2 b5 {should
transpose.}) 7... Be7 $1 ({If we play} 7... b5 {with the bishop still on the
f1-a6 diagonal, White can apply pressure:} 8. a4 c4 9. Bf1 $1 $36) 8. Bc2 (8.
a4 {We are now forced to play the same kind of a game with ...b6 instead of ...
b5, but this is not a problem.} b6 9. Bc2 Bb7 10. d4 Qc7 $132 {Compare to the
main line}) 8... b5 $1 9. d4 Bb7 10. Nbd2 Qc7 $1 {In general we play the quick
...Qc7. In one line it turns out the long castle will be a strong move,
benefiting from not castling short yet.} 11. Nf1 (11. e5 $5 dxe5 12. dxe5 Nd5
13. Ne4 (13. Nf1 $6 {Too passive.} c4 14. Ng3 O-O-O $3 $15 {Black takes over
the initiative with the unexpected long castle!} 15. h4 Nc5) 13... c4 $5 {
Immediately expanding on the queenside.} 14. Bg5 (14. Nd6+ $2 Bxd6 15. exd6
Qxd6 16. Qd4 {This whole idea looks promising, but fails due to a very
concrete reason that we should know:} O-O $3 {Black has a wonderful response
to the kingside attack up his sleeve:} 17. Qh4 (17. Ng5 h6 18. Ne4 Qb6 $17)
17... f5 $15 18. Ng5 h6 19. Rxe6 Rae8 $3 $15 {The big point.} 20. Bxf5 N5f6 $1
{Keeping the queen en prix. More complications follow:} 21. Bf4 Qd5 22. Qh3
hxg5 23. Rd6 g4 $1 24. Bxg4 Qxg2+ 25. Qxg2 Bxg2 26. Bxd7 Nxd7 27. Kxg2 Rxf4 28.
Rxd7 Re2 $15 {White will have to work to hold the endgame.}) (14. Qd4 Qb6 $132)
14... O-O 15. Bxe7 Nxe7 $11 {The d6 square weakness is offest by the
vulnerability of the e5-pawn, e.g.} 16. Nd6 Bxf3 $1 {Initiating tactical
exchanges.} 17. Qxf3 Nxe5 $1 18. Bxh7+ Kxh7 19. Qh5+ Kg8 20. Qxe5 Ng6 21. Qg3
Rad8 22. Rad1 Rd7 23. Ne4 Rxd1 24. Rxd1 Rd8 $132 {The position is pretty
simplified and equal, but there is still some tension left.}) 11... O-O 12. Ng3
{And now we have a few ways to play...} Rfc8 $5 (12... cxd4 $2 {THIS IS WRONG!
We must keep the tension and the possibility to play c5-c4!} 13. cxd4 Rfc8 14.
Bd3 $14) (12... a5 $1 {This is also very good... with nice play on the
queenside.} 13. a4 (13. Bd3 b4 14. cxb4 $2 axb4 $17 15. Bd2 Rfc8) (13. a3 Rfc8
14. Bd3 b4 $132) 13... b4 $132 14. Bd2 Rfc8 15. Rc1 Bf8) 13. Bd3 Bf8 14. Bd2 g6
$1 (14... e5 {is also an option, but ...g6 is on our agenda anyway.} 15. d5 c4
16. Bc2 a5 $132) 15. h3 e5 16. d5 c4 17. Bc2 a5 {A little provocation, but
also a typical move for the structure.} 18. a4 $6 {This is what we wanted to
provoke.} (18. a3 Nc5 19. Nh2 Bg7 $132 {Black has a wonderful Breyer. Remember
about the idea ...Rcb8 and ...Bc8-d7.}) 18... Ba6 $1 $36 {We can develop some
intiative on the queenside, but do not hurry with ...Nc5-d3!} *

