-487,-520,-626,-633,-719,-705]} 1. e4 c5 2. Nf3 d6 3. Bb5+ Nd7 4. O-O a6 5. Bd3
Ngf6 6. Re1 g6 $1 7. c3 Bg7 ({There is an interesting creative idea of} 7...
Bh6 8. Bc2 e5 {, but I have concluded that it's unfortunately not very good
after investigating it.}) 8. Bc2 O-O 9. d4 ({After starting slowly with d3,
White may later not even be able to execute d3-d4 anymore, or regret it if he
does. The following line illustartes this fact:} 9. d3 $2 b5 10. Nbd2 Bb7 11.
Nf1 e5 12. Ng3 (12. Bg5 h6) 12... Re8 $15 13. d4 $2 (13. h3 d5 $15) 13... cxd4
14. cxd4 exd4 15. Nxd4 d5 $3 $19 {White has wasted too much time in the whole
opening phase and is actually already lost, at the very beggining of a direct
skirmish!}) 9... e5 10. a4 {White plays the best move. For other tries, and
for the best reaction to this move, see the theory part.} Qc7 $6 {Ian
Nepomniachtchi either didn't know the variation, or simply chose to play a
less known move to confuse a lower-rated opponent.} (10... exd4 $1 11. cxd4
cxd4 12. Nxd4 Ng4 $3 $132 13. Qxg4 Bxd4) (10... Rb8 $1) 11. dxe5 (11. d5 $1 {
was the way to punish Black's last move.} b6 {Played to stop a4-a5. But White
has a good retort.} (11... c4 12. a5 $14 ({Or} 12. Nbd2 Rb8 13. a5 $14)) 12.
Na3 $1 {Striving for control of the c4-square.} ({A waste of tempo with} 12. h3
$6 {allows} c4 $1 {with a great game for Black all of a sudden.} ({Not} 12...
Rb8 $6 {We will no longer be in time to play ...c4, beacuase White can occupy
this square with the pawn.} 13. c4 $1 b5 14. axb5 axb5 15. cxb5 Rxb5 16. Nc3
$16) 13. Nbd2 Rb8 14. Nf1 b5 15. Ng3 Nc5 16. Be3 Bd7) 12... Ne8 (12... c4 $2 {
is impossible due to} 13. Qe2 $18) 13. b4 $16 {It is White who has the
queenside initiative. The opening has been a failure for Black.}) 11... Nxe5
12. Nxe5 dxe5 13. c4 ({In the case of} 13. Bg5 {Black has the restricting ..c4
idea available in the near future:} Be6 14. Nd2 c4 $15) 13... Bg4 14. f3 Be6
15. Qe2 b5 $1 {A creative tactical trick.} 16. Nd2 $6 {Now Black starts to get
a real initative and later wins convincingly.} ({The point of the last move is}
16. axb5 Bxc4 $1 {Nevertheless, White had a good counter-trick:} 17. b6 $1 $14
(17. Qxc4 $2 axb5 $19)) 16... Nd7 17. axb5 axb5 18. Rxa8 Rxa8 19. cxb5 c4 20.
b3 Qc5+ 21. Kf1 c3 22. Nc4 Qxb5 23. Qd3 Qb4 24. Be3 Bf8 25. Rc1 Rc8 26. Qe2 Nc5
27. Nxe5 Nxb3 28. Rb1 Qa3 29. f4 Nd2+ 30. Bxd2 cxd2 31. Qxd2 Qa2 32. Rc1 Ba3
33. f5 Bxc1 0-1

