{[%evp 0,38,27,33,43,50,80,62,69,47,42,38,58,35,20,-7,6,4,30,-7,8,-9,-11,-4,-4,
5,16,2,-4,-9,-9,-11,-11,-29,-26,-22,-9,-33,-35,-22,-22] This game shows plenty
of incorrect/suboptimal play by both sides. We can learn hwo not to conduct
the game from it!} 1. e4 c5 2. Nf3 d6 3. Bb5+ Nd7 4. Ba4 Ngf6 5. O-O g6 {
I recommend 5...e6, but let's look at this instructive game anyway.} 6. Re1 Bg7
7. c3 O-O 8. d4 e5 9. Bc2 a6 ({I don't like} 9... b5 10. a4 b4 {, but it's also
playable.}) 10. h3 b5 11. a4 Bb7 $6 (11... Rb8 {is more to the point. After
White closes the centre we want ...c4, ...Nc5 and ...Bd7! instead of putting
up with a passive bishop on b7.}) 12. d5 Ne8 $2 {Not a correct choice. Black
needs to play ..c4!} (12... c4 {is the correct idea, which we should be
familiar with.}) 13. axb5 $2 {White releases the tension and the game becomes
harmless. The players soon closed the position and agreed a draw.} ({The
typical idea of} 13. b3 $14 {gives White a serious edge.}) 13... axb5 14. Rxa8
Qxa8 15. Na3 Nc7 16. c4 b4 17. Nb1 Qd8 18. b3 h6 19. Nbd2 Nf6 1/2-1/2

