-648,-702,-761,-761,-781,-816,-29999,-30000] Black played a successful opening,
but a not-so-successful middlegame, prevailing after mistakes by both sides.}
1. e4 c5 2. Nf3 d6 3. Bb5+ Nd7 4. O-O a6 5. Bd3 Ngf6 6. Re1 g6 7. c3 Bg7 8. Bc2
O-O 9. d4 e5 10. d5 b5 11. a4 Nb6 12. b3 Bd7 13. a5 Nc8 {The opening has been a
success, because Black can safely shift to preparinf ...f5 and he will be the
one calling the shots.} 14. c4 Ne7 15. Nbd2 b4 16. Nf1 Ne8 17. Ra2 f5 18. exf5
gxf5 19. Ng3 Ng6 $2 {Alas, this is not correct. The knight should rather keep
supporting the f5-pawn.} ({The preparatory} 19... Ra7 $1 {was strong, e.g.} 20.
Ng5 h6 21. Ne6 Bxe6 22. dxe6 Nc7 23. Qh5 f4 24. Ne4 Nxe6 $13 {with a
double-edged game.}) 20. Ng5 Nf4 $2 {This is even worse. Black is now lost,
but a turn of events decided the game in his favour.} 21. Bxf4 exf4 22. Ne6
Bxe6 23. dxe6 Qg5 24. e7 Rf7 25. Qd5 $6 {Preserves an edge, but complications
are to Black's liking in a bad situation like this.} (25. h4 $1 $18 {was the
precise, not-so-hard way to decide matters.}) 25... fxg3 26. Qxa8 gxf2+ 27.
Kxf2 Bd4+ 28. Kf1 Qf4+ 29. Qf3 Qxh2 30. Re6 $2 {One uncautious move and the
position turns from a win to a loss.} ({After} 30. Bxf5 $1 {White would have
probably prevailed.}) 30... Rg7 $1 $19 {White is helpless.} 31. Be4 Rg3 32. Bd5
Rxf3+ 33. gxf3 Qg1+ 34. Ke2 Kh8 35. Rd2 Bc3 36. Rd1 Qh2+ 37. Kd3 Qb2 38. Rg1
Qd2# 0-1

