177,177,156,156,177,156,295,92,99,99,89,89,89,121,122,-45,-62,-52,21,-17,62,
-378,-146,-85,0,0,0,0,0,0,0,-19,37,0,63,0,397,0,37,-86,44,0,15,30,27]} 1. e4 c5
2. Nf3 d6 3. Bb5+ Nd7 4. O-O a6 5. Bd3 Ngf6 6. c3 g6 7. Re1 (7. Bc2 $1 {
and d4 immediately is why I don't recommend 6...g6 against 6.c3}) 7... Bg7 8.
Bc2 O-O 9. d4 e5 10. h3 b5 11. a4 Bb7 (11... Rb8 {is the accurate move.}) 12.
Nbd2 $2 {White can't play like this, becoming too soft in the centre.} (12. d5
$1 {is the right strategical choice.}) 12... Qc7 $6 ({Black should play the
double capture with immediate problems for White:} 12... cxd4 $1 13. cxd4 exd4
14. Nxd4 Qb6 $15) 13. Nf1 $2 {White allows the double capture again.} (13. d5
$1 {was again to be played. Black should react with} c4 $132) 13... Rac8 $2 {
Black misses the chance for a double capture for good.} 14. d5 $1 {Finally!} c4
15. Be3 Nc5 16. N3d2 Nfd7 ({We should prioritize improving the light-squared
bishop:} 16... Rb8 17. Ng3 ({With} 17. g4 Bc8 {White tries to attack a very
solid pawn structure, and is basically doing herself more harm than good.})
17... Bc8) 17. Ng3 Nb6 18. axb5 axb5 19. h4 Ra8 20. Qe2 Nba4 21. Rab1 Bc8 22.
h5 f5 {Black carries out a commpletely incorrect and premature ...f5 adavance.
She still wins the game later, which is not very relevant. Remember, Black
usually plays ...f5 only in the endgame in these Breyer-type positions!} 23. h6
Bh8 24. exf5 gxf5 25. Nxf5 Bf6 26. Qh5 Ra7 27. Bg5 Bxf5 28. Bxf5 Bxg5 29. Qxg5+
Kh8 30. Re3 Qf7 31. Be6 Nxe6 32. dxe6 Qxe6 33. Rg3 Qf6 34. Qg4 Qxh6 35. Ne4 Rg7
36. Qxg7+ Qxg7 37. Rxg7 Kxg7 38. Nxd6 Rb8 39. Ne4 Kg6 40. f3 Rd8 41. Kf2 Nc5
42. Ke2 Nd3 43. b3 Nf4+ 44. Kf2 Ra8 45. bxc4 bxc4 0-1

