{[%evp 0,60,31,20,41,52,55,42,65,26,8,-15,-24,-26,-15,-19,-8,-8,-8,-21,-12,-24,
-29,-3,-23,-26,-26,-32,-21,-29,-27,-84,-85,-111,-84,-83,-89,-79,-103,-133,-111,
-117,-125,-120,-132,-151,-112,-156,-166,-161,-166,-120,-111,-166,-146,-179,
-181,-217,-148,-214,-188,-453,-453] This blitz game shows the pitfalls of
trying to fish for the b5-pawn for White and an attractive method of reacting
for Black.} 1. e4 c5 2. Nf3 d6 3. Bb5+ Nd7 4. c3 Ngf6 5. Qe2 a6 6. Ba4 e6 7.
O-O b5 8. Bc2 Bb7 9. a4 $6 Be7 (9... c4 $36 {is also interesting.}) 10. Re1 O-O
11. axb5 $6 (11. d4 Qb6 $11) 11... axb5 12. Rxa8 Qxa8 13. Qxb5 $2 {Too greedy.}
Ba6 14. Qa5 Qb7 ({The immediate} 14... c4 $1 $17 {was the best, with a big
clamp and more than enough compensation. ...Nc5 comes and it is hard for White
to solve the big issue of the bishop being stuck on c1.}) 15. Qa4 (15. Qa2 $3 {
is the engine way to salvage the position, but try to find this move,
especcialy in blitz!} c4 16. Na3 Qc7 17. b3 cxb3 18. Bxb3 Nc5 19. Bc4 $1 $11)
15... Ra8 16. Qb3 Qxb3 17. Bxb3 Bd3 18. Na3 Bxe4 {White has lost the greedily
taken pawn and has ended up with development problems and nothing to show in
return.} 19. Ng5 Bd3 20. Bc2 Bxc2 21. Nxc2 c4 $1 {Look at the miserable bishop
on c1!} 22. Nf3 Nc5 23. Rd1 Nfd7 24. Nb4 Ra1 25. Nc2 Ra4 26. Nce1 Nb3 27. Nc2
Ndc5 28. Nfe1 Bg5 29. Nf3 Bh6 30. Na3 Nd3 {White is completely tied down and
hopelessly lost. An impressive punishment for taking on b5!} 0-1

