{[%evp 0,126,21,33,49,52,68,40,79,46,55,1,15,2,5,-2,-18,-19,-3,-3,-10,-26,-6,
-39,-31,-25,-6,-15,-21,-13,4,4,30,-3,19,12,7,-2,3,17,11,-10,10,-2,19,26,20,8,
17,2,9,7,4,26,4,3,4,14,11,3,3,3,15,7,10,17,22,0,12,8,12,0,12,12,21,18,38,22,8,
0,0,0,-7,-22,-22,-19,-14,-19,-26,-29,-15,-15,-15,-38,-14,-124,-120,-138,-75,
-83,-45,-45,-68,-94,-81,-82,-91,-91,-80,-106,-97,-90,-120,-114,-153,-160,-188,
-195,-119,-360,-371,-371,-419,-447,-287,-511,-511,-511,-529] In this very
instructive game Black was patiently exchanging pieces and little by little he
started taking over!... the maneuver of the ...Bg7 to the queenside is very
typical and important to know!} 1. e4 c5 2. Nf3 d6 3. Bb5+ Nd7 4. O-O a6 5. Bd3
Ngf6 6. c3 b5 {This is not my suggested move, but the game transposes later
precisely to our main line.} 7. Bc2 (7. a4 c4 (7... Bb7 8. axb5 axb5 9. Rxa8
Qxa8 10. Bxb5 Bxe4 11. d4 {This is another gambit, where Black has to know much
theory.}) 8. Be2 $1 {is the reason I would not go for this line. We would need
to learn a lot of conrete sharp lines, which is completely unnecessary. We
only risk ending up in a bad position if we forget something.}) 7... Bb7 8. Re1
e6 9. d4 Be7 10. Nbd2 Qc7 11. Nf1 O-O 12. Ng3 Rfe8 13. h3 (13. e5 {is
impossible:} Bxf3 14. Qxf3 dxe5 15. dxe5 Nxe5 $17) 13... Rac8 14. Bd3 Bf8 15.
Bd2 g6 16. Qe2 Bg7 ({This is not yet the moment to play} 16... e5 $2 {,
because White hasn't played a4 yet.} 17. d5 c4 18. Bc2 a5 (18... Nc5 19. b4 $1
{This move is not possible with a4 on the board, which is a crucial difference.
} cxb3 20. axb3 $16) 19. a4 $16) 17. a4 e5 {Now is the time to go for this
move!} 18. d5 c4 19. Bc2 Nc5 {The next step for Black is to remove the bishop
from b7 and put it on d7!...or exchange it!} 20. Nh2 Rb8 21. Ra3 Bc8 22. axb5
axb5 23. Ng4 ({After} 23. Rea1 {Black would finish his plan:} Bd7) 23... Bxg4
$3 {The changed structure will ultimately be the cause of White's downfall.
The knight are at least as strong as the bishop in this closed position.} 24.
hxg4 Ra8 25. Rea1 Rxa3 26. Rxa3 Qb7 27. g5 Nfd7 28. Qd1 Ra8 29. Qa1 Rxa3 30.
Qxa3 Bf8 $3 {Optimalizing the piece placement. The bishop marches all the way
to b6.} 31. Be3 Be7 32. Nf1 Bd8 33. Nd2 Bb6 $15 {Black has the strategical
inititative and managed to outplay White.} 34. Nb1 Bc7 35. Nd2 Bb6 36. Nb1 Bc7
37. Nd2 Kg7 38. g3 Bb6 39. Nb1 Nd3 40. Bxb6 Qxb6 41. Bxd3 cxd3 42. Nd2 Qd8 43.
c4 Qxg5 44. Qxd3 b4 45. Nb3 h5 46. Kg2 h4 47. Kh3 hxg3 48. fxg3 Qd8 49. Kg2 Qa8
50. Qc2 Qa7 51. Qd2 Nf6 52. Qe2 Qa2 53. Nc1 Qb1 54. Nd3 b3 55. Nf2 Qc1 56. Kf3
Nh7 57. Kg2 Ng5 58. g4 Kf6 59. Qd3 Qxb2 60. c5 dxc5 61. d6 Qd4 62. d7 Qxd3 63.
Nxd3 Ke7 {An excellent game by Vachier-Lagrave.} 0-1

