{[%evp 0,64,5,48,103,61,88,65,79,52,54,31,1,-12,10,-14,-12,-11,1,-6,-6,-24,-24,
-30,-5,-55,-55,-68,-68,-64,-58,-106,-82,-101,-123,-104,-104,-124,-123,-135,
-132,-138,-152,-169,-148,-135,-130,-114,-142,-142,-113,-135,-123,-155,-152,
-167,-150,-114,-107,-346,-351,-355,-372,-518,-502,-513,-524] This great game
shows how Black can create many problems if White goes for the very popular
but wrong approach with the passive d3 move!!} 1. e4 c5 2. Nf3 d6 3. Bb5+ Nd7
4. O-O a6 5. Bd3 Ngf6 6. c3 b5 7. Bc2 Bb7 8. d3 $2 ({White should play} 8. Re1
{and d2-d4!}) 8... g6 9. Re1 Bg7 10. Nbd2 O-O 11. Nf1 e5 12. d4 $2 {White plays
d4 now, but he has wasted too much time and has little control over the centre.
The position opens only to Black's benefit.} cxd4 $3 13. cxd4 exd4 $3 {The
famous... double capture!} 14. Nxd4 Re8 15. Ng3 d5 16. exd5 Rxe1+ ({After}
16... Nxd5 17. Rxe8+ Qxe8 $17 {Black is still much better, but the queen is a
bit misplaced, so Khairullin's move is better.}) 17. Qxe1 Nxd5 18. Nb3 Qc7 $19
{Black's pieces completely dominate the open position. Black carried out the
rest of the game flawlessly.} 19. Bd1 Ne5 20. Be2 Re8 21. Qf1 Nc4 22. a4 h5 23.
axb5 axb5 24. Bf3 Nb4 25. Ra7 Nc6 26. Ra2 Qb6 27. Ra1 h4 28. Ne2 h3 29. Rb1
N6e5 30. Bxb7 Qxb7 31. Nbd4 Qe4 32. Ra1 Nd3 0-1

